// ── General bird pool ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
// Used for easy / medium modes. Mix of well-known, charismatic, and obscure.
const BIRDS = [

  // Africa
  { name: "Shoebill", fact: "Stands nearly 1.5 metres tall and stares at prey with both eyes forward like an owl — extremely unusual for a bird. It hunts lungfish by freezing motionless in swamps for hours, then striking with a bill that can decapitate its catch.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/46952988/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Secretary Bird", fact: "Kills snakes by stamping on them with feet that deliver a force five times its own body weight — fast enough that the snake cannot react. Despite being a raptor, it spends most of its life walking, covering up to 20 km a day on foot.", photo: "" },
  { name: "Hammerkop", fact: "Builds the largest nest of any bird relative to its size — a roofed fortress of sticks, mud and grass up to 1.5 metres across that can hold the weight of a grown adult. Pairs build up to five of these in a single year, often for no apparent reason.", photo: "" },
  { name: "Marabou Stork", fact: "Has a hollow leg bone connected to its lungs so it can use its legs as a radiator to cool blood in African heat. Its bald head and neck stay cleaner when plunged deep inside carcasses, and it can eat burning charcoal and old leather without apparent ill effect.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/48113837/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "African Fish Eagle", fact: "The call of the African Fish Eagle is so iconic it is used as a generic 'Africa' sound effect in films set on other continents. It snatches fish from the surface with its talons while barely getting its feet wet, then flies off with a meal in under three seconds.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/339871833/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Lilac-breasted Roller", fact: "Gets its name from the spectacular rolling dive it performs during courtship — plummeting and twisting while calling loudly. It can see ultraviolet light, which reveals tracks and urine trails left by insects and lizards invisible to human eyes.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/8050/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Southern Ground Hornbill", fact: "Lives in groups where only the dominant pair breeds, and helpers — including non-relatives — wait up to a decade for a chance to raise chicks. The group buries food caches and can remember locations for years. Individuals can live past 70.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/64757984/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Hoopoe", fact: "The female and chicks produce a foul-smelling liquid from their preen gland that coats the nest, deterring predators and bacteria. Despite the stench, it was considered sacred in ancient Egypt and appears in hieroglyphics. It also probes soil with its bill like a precision sewing machine.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/60494705/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Cape Sugarbird", fact: "Found only in South Africa's fynbos, it pollinates proteas so efficiently that the plants have evolved flowers matching the exact curve of its bill. The male's tail can be twice its body length and he carries it even while hovering in strong winds.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/159555798/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Ostrich", fact: "The largest living bird and the fastest running bird on Earth, reaching 70 km/h in a sprint. Its eye is bigger than its brain — each eyeball measures 5 cm across. Rather than burying its head in the sand, it lays its head flat on the ground to hide.", photo: "" },
  { name: "Saddle-billed Stork", fact: "One of Africa's tallest flying birds at up to 150 cm, with a bill so vivid — red, black and yellow with a yellow 'saddle' — that early explorers thought it must have been painted. Males and females are identical except for eye colour: males have brown eyes, females yellow.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/339545431/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "African Skimmer", fact: "Flies low over rivers with its lower mandible slicing through the water like a plow blade. The moment it feels a fish, the upper bill snaps shut in a split second. Its lower mandible grows faster than the upper to compensate for constant wear from dragging through water.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/141963797/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Pel's Fishing Owl", fact: "One of the world's largest owls, specialising entirely in fish. Unlike other owls it has no sound-dampening feathers — waterproofing matters more than silence when hunting fish — and its feet have spiny scales for gripping slippery prey. Its call is a deep booming moan heard a kilometre away.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/59683337/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Hartlaub's Turaco", fact: "The only birds to have true red and green pigments in their feathers — most birds fake these colours with structure. Turacos make their own copper-based pigments called turacin (red) and turacoverdin (green) that dissolve slightly in water, giving the illusion of bleeding colour in heavy rain.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/207915565/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Superb Starling", fact: "A common East African bird so brilliantly coloured — metallic blue-green above, chestnut below, with a white chest band — that tourists often mistake it for an exotic rarity. Despite its looks it's a bold opportunist that will steal food from café tables.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/329009302/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Kori Bustard", fact: "Possibly the heaviest flying bird on Earth, with males reaching 19 kg. During courtship the male inflates its neck to balloon size and fans its white undertail feathers until it looks twice its normal size. It eats toxic plants and venomous snakes without apparent harm.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/73258609/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Grey Crowned Crane", fact: "The only crane that roosts in trees — its hind toe is long enough to grip branches. It stamps its feet while foraging to flush insects, and its golden crown of bristled feathers vibrates in response to sound, possibly acting as a resonator for its booming call.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/261339008/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Rosy-faced Lovebird", fact: "In cold desert nights pairs tuck their heads under each other's wings and sleep pressed together, regulating each other's body temperature. Females carry nesting material tucked into their rump feathers rather than in their bills — a method unique among parrots.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/397224666/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Black-and-white Casqued Hornbill", fact: "A large rainforest hornbill of Central Africa that relies on figs and uses its casque — a hollow ridge on the bill — to amplify its resonant calls through the forest. Pairs remain bonded for life and the male seals the female into the nest cavity with mud and droppings.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/111631900/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "African Pitta", fact: "A jewel of the rainforest floor — glossy blue, green, red and black — yet so secretive that it was once considered rare. It is now known to be a common migrant that simply hides perfectly in leaf litter. It hammers snails against anvil stones to break the shells.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/176877645/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Martial Eagle", fact: "Africa's largest eagle, powerful enough to knock a grown person off their feet. It can spot prey from 5 km away and has been documented killing small antelopes, monitor lizards and young baboons. Its population has crashed due to persecution and habitat loss.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/397866680/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Bateleur", fact: "Spends up to eight hours a day airborne, covering 300–400 km while barely flapping. Its name is French for 'street performer' — a reference to its rocking, acrobatic flight. The bare red face skin flushes darker when the bird is agitated or excited.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/261340111/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Namaqua Sandgrouse", fact: "Males fly up to 80 km to a waterhole, wade in, and soak their specially adapted belly feathers — which can hold 15–20 ml of water like a sponge. They fly back and the chicks drink directly from the feathers. Chicks can do this from day one.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/62348197/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Long-crested Eagle", fact: "Its extraordinarily long floppy head plumes — up to 15 cm — give it a permanently surprised expression and bounce comically as it flies. Despite looking dramatic it is a specialist rodent hunter, eating almost nothing but voles and other small mammals.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/41737833/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Pennant-winged Nightjar", fact: "The breeding male grows two inner wing feathers that extend up to 50 cm beyond the wingtip as white trailing streamers. He flies with these huge pennants fluttering behind him at dusk to attract females. After breeding season he moults them off and looks like a completely different bird.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/58132532/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Black Heron", fact: "Hunts by spreading both wings into a perfect black umbrella over the water, creating a patch of shade. Fish swim into it seeking shelter from the sun, and the heron picks them off. It is the only animal known to create a tool entirely from its own body to lure prey.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/176287954/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Greater Honeyguide", fact: "The only bird known to actively guide humans to food. Using a distinctive chattering call and fluttering flight, it leads honey-hunters to bees' nests — sometimes over a kilometre — then waits for them to break the hive open before eating the wax and larvae left behind. The partnership is ancient enough to have its own traditional signals in Mozambique.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/59383565/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Long-tailed Widowbird", fact: "The male's tail feathers reach 50 cm — four times its body length — and he hauls them through the air in a slow, laboured display flight above the savannah. Scientists who glued on artificial extensions found those males attracted dramatically more females, confirming the tail is pure sexual advertising at an honest cost.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/183526953/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "African Broadbill", fact: "Performs one of the strangest courtship displays in Africa: the male flies in tight circles around a branch so fast his wings create a mechanical purring sound, then suddenly freezes and puffs himself into a round blob to show off his vivid purple throat patch.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/151947/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "African Finfoot", fact: "An extremely shy waterbird that swims low in the water like a grebe but climbs into waterside vegetation to escape. The female carries newly hatched chicks in special pouches of skin under her wings while swimming — discovered by accident when a bird was spooked and chicks tumbled out.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/1840252/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Sunbird Asity", fact: "A Madagascan oddity distantly related to broadbills but looking exactly like a sunbird — a striking example of convergent evolution. The male has a vivid wattle of electric blue and green bare skin around the eye that inflates during breeding season and deflates completely afterwards.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/55348934/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Lappet-faced Vulture", fact: "The most dominant vulture at a carcass in Africa — other species wait for it to open the hide before they can feed. The bare red folds of skin on its face help it look intimidating. It eats skin, tendons and bone fragments that other scavengers cannot process.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/333938254/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Hooded Vulture", fact: "One of the smallest African vultures, with a thin bill perfectly sized for probing into crevices and eye sockets that larger vultures can't reach. It has recently learned to follow fishing trawlers and scavenge at rubbish dumps, but is still one of the fastest-declining birds in Africa.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/52848887/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Verreaux's Eagle", fact: "One of the most specialised predators on Earth — up to 98% of its diet is rock hyrax, a rabbit-sized mammal. So dependent on hyrax colonies that when they disappear from an area the eagles abandon their territory rather than switch prey. Pairs use the same cliff nest for decades, adding sticks each year until it is enormous.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/305836949/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Taita Falcon", fact: "A tiny torpedo-shaped falcon that nests exclusively on sheer cliff faces, including inside Batoka Gorge at Victoria Falls. Fewer than 200 are thought to exist globally, yet it is so fast and agile it regularly catches swifts — themselves masters of aerial speed.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/31116111/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "White-fronted Bee-eater", fact: "Lives in extended family groups where non-breeding helpers assist the dominant pair — but also 'kidnaps' young from other pairs within the colony, harassing them until a fledgling abandons its own parents and follows its abductors, boosting the kidnapper's own reproductive success.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/263821166/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "African Jacana", fact: "Walks on floating lily pads on extraordinarily long toes that spread its weight like snowshoes. Sex roles are reversed: females are larger, hold territories and mate with several males. Each male incubates eggs and rears chicks alone — tucking the tiny chicks under his wings and wading to safety with their legs dangling out.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/179809856/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Knysna Turaco", fact: "A brilliantly coloured forest turaco of South Africa's Garden Route whose emerald green plumage comes from turacoverdin, a copper-based pigment found in no other animal on Earth. It runs along branches with surprising speed and agility rather than flying between them.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/402888885/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "African Openbill", fact: "Its bill has a permanent gap when closed — not a deformity but a precision tool. The edges of the mandibles meet only at the tip, forming curved forceps perfectly shaped for gripping and twisting open apple snail shells and freshwater mussels without crushing them.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/416330652/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Palm-nut Vulture", fact: "The only vulture that eats primarily plant material — it feeds mainly on the husks of oil palm and raphia palm fruits. This vegetarian diet allows it to thrive in dense forest where other vultures rarely venture. Despite being a vulture it also readily eats fish, frogs and crabs.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/450903960/medium.jpg" },

  // Asia
  { name: "Indian Peafowl", fact: "The male's train isn't his tail — it's elongated back plumage. Each feather has an iridescent 'eye' made not from pigment but from nanostructures that reflect light differently at every angle. The train rattles and shimmers during display and produces infrasound below human hearing that females may sense through their feet.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/165318600/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Himalayan Monal", fact: "The national bird of Nepal, the male is arguably the most colourful bird in Asia — covered in metallic green, purple, copper and blue, with no two patches the same hue. It digs through deep snow with its heavy curved bill to reach roots and tubers at altitudes above 4,000 metres.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/374965708/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Red-crowned Crane", fact: "One of the rarest cranes on Earth, with fewer than 3,000 remaining. In Japanese culture it symbolises longevity and fidelity, appearing on the 1,000-yen note. Pairs bond for life and perform elaborate synchronised dances — leaping and calling in perfect unison — that strengthen the bond year after year.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/122932380/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Oriental Pied Hornbill", fact: "Like all hornbills, the male seals the female inside a tree hollow with mud and droppings, leaving only a slit through which he passes food for months. The female uses the enforced isolation to safely moult all her flight feathers at once — something she couldn't do while exposed to predators.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/208950228/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Sarus Crane", fact: "The world's tallest flying bird, standing up to 180 cm. Sacred in India and depicted in ancient Sanskrit literature as a symbol of faithful love, because pairs reputedly grieve when a partner dies. Farmers deliberately protect nesting Sarus cranes in rice paddies, believing harming one brings misfortune.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/240246165/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Indian Roller", fact: "The state bird of three Indian states, famous for its dazzling aerial display in which it rolls and tumbles to reveal brilliant turquoise underwings — colour invisible when the bird is perched. Farmers welcome it because it follows tractors to snatch exposed insects and earthworms.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/289373974/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Painted Stork", fact: "Feeds by wading with its partly open bill submerged and sweeping it side to side, snapping shut purely by touch the instant a fish brushes it. The faint pink flush on its wing tips deepens during breeding season — the only stork to change colour seasonally.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/84838910/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Indian Paradise Flycatcher", fact: "The male comes in two forms — white or chestnut — and grows two central tail feathers that stream up to 30 cm behind him. He fans and waves them during courtship while the female sits apparently unmoved, assessing how long he can maintain the performance.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/6761392/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Siberian Crane", fact: "Makes one of the longest migrations of any bird — breeding in remote Arctic Russia and wintering almost entirely at China's Poyang Lake. With fewer than 4,000 left, its survival hinges on a single wetland. It uses touch rather than sight to probe underwater for the plant roots it eats.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/42649395/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Great Hornbill", fact: "The hollow casque on the bill acts as a resonator for its deep booming call, which carries far through the dense forest. The male feeds the sealed-in female up to 150 times a day, passing food piece by piece through the narrow slit. Pairs stay together for life and can live over 50 years.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/265662265/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Brahminy Kite", fact: "Considered sacred in Bali, where it is the divine vehicle of Vishnu, and revered across Hindu and Buddhist cultures throughout Southeast Asia. It scavenges shorelines and rubbish dumps with equal comfort, but also hunts live prey — snatching fish, frogs and even bats with a sudden plunging strike.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/49857906/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Sri Lanka Frogmouth", fact: "One of the world's most perfectly camouflaged birds. By day it sits motionless on a mossy branch with its eyes slitted and bill raised, looking precisely like a broken stub of bark. It is endemic to Sri Lanka and the Western Ghats and was unknown to science until 1849.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/177141455/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Stork-billed Kingfisher", fact: "One of the largest kingfishers in Asia, with a bill so disproportionately huge — red, massive and cartoon-like — that it seems physically improbable. It dives into rivers to catch large fish but also eats lizards, frogs and small birds, waiting motionless on a branch before plunging.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/233705452/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Blue Pitta", fact: "A jewel of the forest floor — electric blue, orange and black — that is heard far more often than seen. It hops through leaf litter turning over dead leaves with its bill in search of earthworms. Males sing persistently at dawn from a favourite perch, but disappear into undergrowth almost instantly.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/257120450/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Jerdon's Courser", fact: "A nocturnal wader so rarely seen that it was believed extinct for over 80 years before being rediscovered in 1986 in a steep rocky gorge in India. It forages only at night on boulder-strewn streamsides and retreats to rocky crevices by day, making it almost impossible to survey.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/9677256/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Malabar Trogon", fact: "The male is crimson below and iridescent dark blue-green above, but sits so still in the forest shade that it vanishes despite its colours. Endemic to the Western Ghats and Sri Lanka, it nests in tree cavities it excavates itself, using its serrated bill like a saw.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/50602727/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Spoon-billed Sandpiper", fact: "Its spatula-shaped bill is unique among waders and acts like a sensitive metal detector, sweeping through soft mud and snapping shut on tiny invertebrates. Critically endangered, with perhaps only 500 remaining, it migrates from Arctic Russia to Bangladesh and Myanmar along a flyway that has lost most of its stopover wetlands.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/246421543/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Milky Stork", fact: "A coastal stork of mangroves and tidal mudflats in Southeast Asia that feeds with its bill partly open, feeling for fish and crabs by touch. Its population has plummeted as mangroves are cleared for aquaculture, and it now survives mainly in a handful of protected sites in Sumatra.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/181076647/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Bar-headed Goose", fact: "Regularly flies directly over the Himalayas at altitudes above 7,000 metres — sometimes passing over Everest. Its haemoglobin binds oxygen far more efficiently than that of lowland birds, and its heart rate during this extreme exertion is higher than any other bird ever measured.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/93376717/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Mandarin Duck", fact: "The male's courtship plumage includes a pair of orange 'sail' feathers that project upright from the wing — used purely for display and moulted immediately after the breeding season. Considered a symbol of marital fidelity in China and Japan, though pairs actually separate each year and choose new mates.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/171955255/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Walden's Hornbill", fact: "Critically endangered and confined to a handful of Philippine islands, it was named for an English ornithologist and is so rarely photographed that basic facts about its behaviour remain unknown. Its casque and bill are brighter yellow-orange in males, and pairs engage in noisy aerial chases through the forest canopy.", photo: "" },
  { name: "Bornean Bristlehead", fact: "Possibly the strangest bird in Borneo — a chunky black-and-red forest bird whose bare red head is studded with small fleshy knobs, giving it a warty, alien appearance. It has no close living relatives; its whole family contains just this one species. It travels in noisy flocks and the knobs' function remains unknown.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/58447940/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Wrinkled Hornbill", fact: "Has a deeply corrugated bill and casque that makes it look like it has been badly crumpled. Found only in the lowland rainforests of Borneo and the Malay Peninsula, it is heavily dependent on old-growth trees with cavities large enough to seal a female inside for incubation.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/13808689/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Gurney's Pitta", fact: "Once thought extinct, rediscovered in Thailand in 1986 and again in Myanmar in 2003. The male is a mosaic of deep blue, yellow and black. It lives in lowland rainforest that has been almost entirely logged, and surveys suggest only a few hundred individuals remain.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/90010206/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Philippine Eagle", fact: "One of the world's largest eagles, with a wingspan up to 220 cm and eyes described by researchers as 'almost human' in expressiveness. It hunts flying lemurs through dense canopy at speed. Critically endangered, with under 800 left, and the national symbol of the Philippines.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/30332073/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Palawan Peacock-Pheasant", fact: "The male carries an iridescent blue-green fan of tail feathers covered in metallic 'eyes', which he fans open and rocks from side to side during courtship while the female circles to examine each eye from every angle. Found only on the Philippine island of Palawan.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/45924388/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Storm's Stork", fact: "One of the world's rarest storks, with probably fewer than 500 remaining. Confined to undisturbed lowland rivers in Borneo, Sumatra and Malaysia, it nests in huge trees overhanging the water. Almost nothing is known about its breeding behaviour because it is so rarely observed.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/49854976/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Crested Serpent Eagle", fact: "Specialises almost entirely in snakes and lizards, using its broad rounded wings to slow-glide over the forest canopy while watching for prey below. When it spots a snake it drops and pins it with powerful feet before biting the back of the skull — immune to most snake venoms it encounters.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/157108171/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Cheer Pheasant", fact: "A long-tailed pheasant of steep Himalayan hillsides whose male has 18 tail feathers — more than any other pheasant. Its name comes from its call, a loud ringing 'chir-chir-chirwa', not its demeanour. It is so good at hiding in rocky scrub that locals describe it as 'impossible to find twice.'", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/65046757/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Satyr Tragopan", fact: "The male has a brilliant crimson breast studded with white spots like a polka-dot spotlight. During courtship he inflates two blue horns on his head and a bib of brilliant blue and red skin that expands to the size of a handkerchief — then suddenly flashes it at the female from behind a rock.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/174249254/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Temminck's Tragopan", fact: "Found high in the Eastern Himalayas, the male performs one of the most spectacular displays in the bird world: crouching low, spreading his spotted wings as a backdrop, and inflating an extraordinary patterned bib of blue, red and white skin that hangs down from his throat like a painted flag.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/66364877/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Green Peafowl", fact: "Larger and arguably more elegant than the Indian Peafowl, with iridescent green and bronze plumage and a neat, upright crest. Unlike its cousin, both sexes carry long train feathers. Once widespread across Southeast Asia, it has been hunted and its wetland habitat drained until only scattered populations remain.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/210255393/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Wilson's Bird-of-Paradise", fact: "Has a bare turquoise-blue crown — one of the only birds with genuinely blue skin rather than blue feathers. The male painstakingly clears the forest floor of every leaf before performing his display, creating a stage. The curling green tail wires are held in a tight spiral at rest and flung outward during display.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/391359474/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Wallace's Standardwing", fact: "Named for Alfred Russel Wallace, who discovered it on the island of Bacan in 1858 and wrote that it was 'more like a work of art than a natural production.' The male carries two long white breast plumes — the 'standards' — that he erects and vibrates while hanging upside down in a communal display tree.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/50198870/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Maleo", fact: "Lays eggs six times the size of a chicken egg in geothermal or sun-warmed sand, then abandons them. The chick digs out alone, tunnelling upward through half a metre of sand over several days, and emerges fully feathered and able to fly within hours — having received no parental care whatsoever.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/71262338/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Nicobar Pigeon", fact: "The closest living relative of the extinct Dodo and Rodrigues Solitaire — the sole survivor of a lineage of giant island pigeons. It has iridescent hackles of green, copper and blue cascading from its neck, and a small white tail. It travels in flocks between islands up to 400 km apart to find fruiting trees.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/57343379/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Black-naped Pheasant-Pigeon", fact: "A secretive ground-pigeon of Papua New Guinea's Fergusson Island, discovered only in 1882 and then not photographed alive in the wild until 2023, when camera traps finally captured it after an exhaustive community-led search. It lives in dense montane forest and walks rather than flies.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/478067618/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Halmahera Paradise Crow", fact: "A glossy blue-black bird related to birds-of-paradise, found only on the Indonesian island of Halmahera. The male has a vivid red iris and performs a hopping display in the forest understory. So little is known about it that researchers still don't fully understand its display or nesting behaviour.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/375145945/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Spot-billed Pelican", fact: "Has a distinctive pink and blue-spotted bill pouch used to scoop fish like a net. Unlike other pelicans it often breeds colonially in trees far from water, and groups fish cooperatively, beating the surface with their wings to herd shoals into shallow water before plunging their bills in unison.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/230657515/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Pied Kingfisher", fact: "The world's largest kingfisher that hovers. It can hang stationary over water for up to 30 seconds, vibrating its wings at 9 beats per second while scanning below, then plunges straight down. Because it doesn't need a perch over water, it can fish rivers and lakes with no overhanging trees at all.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/442581673/medium.jpeg" },

  // Australasia & New Zealand
  { name: "Cassowary", fact: "Has a blade-like inner claw up to 12 cm long that it uses to disembowel threats with a single kick. Despite being the world's most dangerous bird, it is a crucial rainforest gardener — the only animal large enough to swallow and disperse the seeds of over 150 tree species.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/415762966/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Kea", fact: "The world's only alpine parrot, and one of the most intelligent birds alive. Keas solve multi-step puzzles, play in snow for fun, and have been filmed dismantling car windscreen wipers and stealing wallets from tourists. They make decisions collectively and have been observed using probability to improve their odds.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/7022252/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Kiwi", fact: "The only bird with nostrils at the tip of its bill, used to sniff out earthworms underground like a mammal. Its feathers are more like coarse hair than plumage, and it has no visible tail. Its egg is proportionally the largest of any bird — up to 20% of the female's body weight.", photo: "" },
  { name: "Tawny Frogmouth", fact: "Not an owl — it's related to nightjars. By day it freezes motionless on a branch with its bill pointed upward and eyes almost closed, looking exactly like a broken stub of wood. The camouflage is so effective that researchers have walked within arm's reach without noticing it.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/31726985/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Superb Lyrebird", fact: "The world's greatest vocal mimic: it accurately reproduces chainsaws, car alarms, camera shutters, crying babies and other birds. The male spends years perfecting his display before breeding, and during courtship vibrates his extraordinary lace-like tail over his entire body like a shimmering silver veil.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/204606797/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Rifleman", fact: "New Zealand's smallest bird and one of its most ancient — sole survivor of a lineage that diverged from all other birds over 80 million years ago. The male is an electric iridescent green so vivid it seems to glow; the female is streaky brown. They chip insistently through bark in search of insects.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/1192923/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Laughing Kookaburra", fact: "The famous 'jungle laugh' is a territorial call used by family groups at dawn and dusk, often triggering neighbouring groups to call back in a domino effect. Despite the name it lives in dry woodland, not jungle. It kills snakes by carrying them high in the air and dropping them onto rocks.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/26389611/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Kakapo", fact: "The world's heaviest parrot and the only flightless one. Males gather on hilltop 'leks' and boom from bowl-shaped depressions in the ground — the infrasound travels for kilometres. It is so critically endangered that every individual has a name; intensive management has raised the population from 51 to over 200.", photo: "" },
  { name: "Satin Bowerbird", fact: "Males spend years collecting blue objects — bottle caps, pen lids, flowers, feathers — to decorate a stick bower. He arranges them carefully and has been caught stealing from neighbours. Females prefer males whose bowers contain the most blue items and who are best at replacing stolen ones.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/304567604/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Regent Bowerbird", fact: "The male is a startling black and golden-yellow, among the most vividly patterned birds in Australia. He makes a grey paint from a mix of saliva and chewed plant material, which he applies to the walls of his bower with a wad of bark used as a brush — one of the very few tool-using birds.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/57257557/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Tooth-billed Bowerbird", fact: "Instead of building a decorated bower, the male clears a patch of forest floor and tiles it with large fresh leaves, all placed upside down with their pale undersides facing up. He replaces them as they wilt. The 'tooth' on his bill is used to cut these leaves from branches.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/177308057/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Vogelkop Bowerbird", fact: "Builds the most structurally complex bower of any animal: a conical thatched hut up to a metre tall with a doorway, fronted by a lawn of moss decorated with coloured piles of fruit, flowers, beetles and fungi — each colour group in its own cluster. Different males develop distinct aesthetic styles.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/382050548/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Raggiana Bird-of-Paradise", fact: "The national symbol of Papua New Guinea, its cascading orange-red plumes were so sought-after for European hats in the 19th century that early naturalists suspected the bird had no feet, since specimens arrived without them. Males compete in communal trees, displaying simultaneously to silent females.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/51251186/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "King Bird-of-Paradise", fact: "The smallest bird-of-paradise and arguably the most extravagant. The male has two wiry tail shafts that end in spiralling green discs, which he swings like pendulums. He displays by hanging upside down and expanding his fan-shaped flank plumes into perfect white circles.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/75407307/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Western Parotia", fact: "Grows six wire-like head plumes tipped with reflective discs. During courtship it transforms itself into a black ballerina — fluffing its flank feathers into a skirt and pivoting in precise circles for minutes at a time. The breast feathers are nanoscale structures that reflect light like a supermatte black.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/59228142/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "King-of-Saxony Bird-of-Paradise", fact: "The male's two head plumes — each twice his body length, decorated with a row of enamel-blue flags — have no counterpart in the animal kingdom. Early scientists who received specimens refused to believe they were real and assumed taxidermists had added them from some other creature.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/67592295/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Blue Bird-of-Paradise", fact: "Performs its display entirely upside down, hanging from a branch and slowly expanding two long blue tail wires while swaying rhythmically. The black breast feathers part to reveal a pulsing iridescent blue oval. The entire display looks like something from a fever dream.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/67592753/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Twelve-wired Bird-of-Paradise", fact: "The flank feathers end in 12 bare wire-like filaments that the male repeatedly presses against the face of the female while displaying. Scientists still don't fully understand why — it may be a tactile assessment or a way of forcing her to keep her eyes on him.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/65191888/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Magnificent Riflebird", fact: "The male stretches his wings into a perfect arc and bobs his head to flash his iridescent throat, which seems to glow from within. The wing feathers are shaped to produce a sharp rasping sound as he raises them. Females have been observed mimicking this display themselves.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/177764124/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Victoria Crowned Pigeon", fact: "The world's largest pigeon — roughly the size of a turkey — and the only one with a permanent crest. The fan of lacy blue-grey feathers tipped with white is raised in alarm, lowered in submission, and waved in courtship. Males boom deeply like a large drum when territorial.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/3206857/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Palm Cockatoo", fact: "The only non-human animal known to use a tool for a musical purpose: the male picks up a stick or nut and drums it rhythmically against a hollow tree to attract females — producing a beat. Each male has his own consistent tempo and drumming style, similar to how human musicians develop a personal feel.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/256916871/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Gang-gang Cockatoo", fact: "The male has a vivid scarlet head and crest that wobbles as he feeds — looking permanently perplexed. It makes a distinctive sound described as a wine cork being pulled from a bottle. Pairs are devoted and groom each other constantly; males help incubate and brood the chicks through the night.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/259067709/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Glossy Black-Cockatoo", fact: "The quietest and most docile of Australia's black cockatoos. Females are flecked with yellow-orange patches that disappear entirely after their first moult into adult plumage, making females look almost identical to males. It feeds almost exclusively on the seeds of one or two species of sheoak.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/157561221/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Yellow-tailed Black-Cockatoo", fact: "Flocks of these large, wailing birds drifting through eucalyptus forests are one of Australia's most atmospheric sounds. They rip apart tree branches with their powerful bills to reach wood-boring beetle larvae — leaving the forest littered with debris that reveals where they've been feeding.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/266820660/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Swift Parrot", fact: "One of only three migratory parrots in the world. It breeds only in Tasmania and winters on the Australian mainland, crossing 300 km of ocean twice a year. Critically endangered — its entire population depends on the Tasmanian blue gum for nesting and sugar gliders have learned to raid its nests.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/332002192/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Orange-bellied Parrot", fact: "One of the rarest birds on Earth, with fewer than 50 adults surviving in the wild. It breeds only in a tiny area of southwest Tasmania and winters on the mainland. Despite an intensive captive breeding and release programme, it remains critically endangered and has not recovered.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/218697305/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Pesquet's Parrot", fact: "Has a bare red face like a vulture — unusual in parrots, but an adaptation for eating sticky figs without getting feathers hopelessly gummed. It is sometimes called the Dracula Parrot for its black-and-red plumage and gothic appearance. Found only in New Guinea's montane forests.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/449330094/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Eclectus Parrot", fact: "The male is vivid green; the female is brilliant red and blue. So different are they that ornithologists classified them as separate species for 150 years. The female controls a hollow tree cavity and may have several males bringing her food simultaneously — while she decides which to mate with.", photo: "" },
  { name: "Emu", fact: "Australia's largest bird is flightless but can run at 50 km/h. The male incubates the eggs and raises the chicks alone, not eating or drinking for up to 56 days during incubation — losing a third of his body weight. Emus can swim across rivers and have been known to travel 1,000 km following rain.", photo: "" },
  { name: "Wedge-tailed Eagle", fact: "Australia's largest bird of prey, with a wingspan up to 2.3 metres. It can soar for hours without a wingbeat, rising on thermals to altitudes where it disappears from sight. Once persecuted as a livestock killer, it was legal to shoot them until 1974 in Western Australia — with millions killed.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/124639106/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Australian Brushturkey", fact: "Builds a mound of rotting vegetation up to 4 metres tall and monitors the internal temperature obsessively, adding or removing material to maintain exactly 33°C. The male uses his bill as a thermometer accurate to half a degree. Chicks hatch fully developed and must dig out alone through a metre of compost.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/50152867/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Malleefowl", fact: "Like the Brushturkey, it builds a compost incubator — but in a much drier environment where decomposing material is scarce. A pair spends 11 months of the year maintaining their mound, opening it each morning to release heat and closing it each afternoon to retain warmth as outside temperatures plunge.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/71922706/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Plains-wanderer", fact: "Looks like a quail but is actually the sole member of an ancient lineage with no close relatives. The female is more boldly patterned than the male and holds the territory while the male incubates eggs and raises chicks alone. It sits perfectly still when threatened, trusting its camouflage, and is critically endangered.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/423273683/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Night Parrot", fact: "Australia's most mysterious bird — widely thought extinct for over a century before being photographed alive in 2013. It inhabits remote spinifex grasslands, flies only at night, and is so secretive that almost nothing is known about its ecology. Every confirmed sighting is considered a significant event.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/106799811/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Gouldian Finch", fact: "Comes in three naturally occurring colour forms — red-faced, black-faced and yellow-faced — that determine personality as well as looks. Pairs choose mates partly based on face colour because mismatched pairs produce more stressed offspring. The young are born with blue phosphorescent spots inside their mouths to guide parents feeding them in dark nests.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/209771912/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Splendid Fairywren", fact: "The male is an implausibly vivid cobalt blue, but maintains a 'harem' of dull brown females and helpers. Most chicks in any nest are fathered by males from neighbouring territories — the female secretly mates with better-looking males while her social partner provides all the parental care.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/247298227/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Noisy Scrubbird", fact: "Once thought extinct, rediscovered in 1961 in a tiny patch of dense coastal scrub in Western Australia. The male's territorial call is so loud it causes physical pain at close range. It is almost entirely flightless, running through low vegetation like a mouse, and rarely emerges into the open.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/253989713/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Powerful Owl", fact: "Australia's largest owl, with eyes so large and forward-facing it has unusually good binocular depth perception for hunting through cluttered forest. It often roosts during the day clutching the previous night's prey — sometimes a whole ringtail possum — in one foot, resuming the meal after dark.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/29556124/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Apostlebird", fact: "Lives in stable groups of around 12 birds — hence the name — in which all members share incubation and chick-rearing duties. The group makes group decisions about when to move, always roosting together in a tight bundle. They are extremely bold and will steal food from picnickers.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/54692600/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Chowchilla", fact: "A large ground-thrush of Queensland's rainforest whose explosive call — a piercing 'chow-chilla' duet between paired birds — erupts at dawn and can be heard over 500 metres away. It spends its days raking through leaf litter with both feet simultaneously, like someone frantically shuffling backwards.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/512810886/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Takahe", fact: "Believed extinct for 50 years before being rediscovered in a remote New Zealand valley in 1948. This large, flightless rail has powerful blue-green plumage and a massive red bill. Intensive conservation management — including predator control and egg fostering — has slowly rebuilt the population to over 500.", photo: "" },
  { name: "Wrybill", fact: "The only bird in the world with a bill that curves sideways — always to the right. It uses this asymmetric tool to probe under stones in riverbeds for insect larvae. It breeds only in New Zealand's South Island braided rivers and migrates to North Island estuaries in winter.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/448012090/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Black Stilt", fact: "The world's rarest wading bird, with fewer than 200 remaining. Found only in New Zealand's South Island braided rivers, it has been devastated by introduced predators. It is the focus of a captive breeding and headstarting programme that hand-raises chicks and releases them before predators learn to target them.", photo: "" },
  { name: "New Zealand Bellbird", fact: "When Captain Cook landed in New Zealand, the dawn chorus of bellbirds was so loud that sailors woke in astonishment, describing it as almost deafeningly beautiful — 'the most melodious wild music I have ever heard.' The female has a thin white whisker stripe; the male's head is a deep iridescent purple-green.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/1179646/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Hihi", fact: "The only bird that mates face-to-face, like humans. Males are highly aggressive and females often struggle to escape them — leading to conservation managers introducing rubber toys and distractions at nest boxes to give females control over mating. Males have disproportionately large testes for a songbird.", photo: "" },
  { name: "Kokako", fact: "Has one of the most haunting calls in the bird world — a slow, organ-like duet between pairs that carries through dense New Zealand forest at dawn. The blue facial wattles droop like a sad clown's cheeks, but the voice is extraordinary: researchers have described it as sounding like 'a sad monk.'", photo: "" },
  { name: "Saddleback", fact: "Named for the chestnut 'saddle' across its back, contrasting with jet-black plumage. It has tiny vestigial wings almost useless for sustained flight. New Zealand's early forests were so safe that flightlessness evolved multiple times — then cats, stoats and rats arrived and nearly wiped it out.", photo: "" },
  { name: "Kaka", fact: "A forest parrot of New Zealand that uses its flexible tongue to extract nectar and its powerful bill to rip apart dead wood for grubs. Males and females have entirely different roles: males feed females during incubation, sometimes travelling kilometres to find food and returning to pass it mouth-to-mouth.", photo: "" },
  { name: "Weka", fact: "A flightless New Zealand rail with the boldness of a small terrier. It will steal shiny objects from campsites, untie bootlaces and investigate anything edible with fearless curiosity. It's an effective predator of small lizards and invertebrates, and has colonised offshore islands — sometimes too enthusiastically.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/204782403/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "New Zealand Dotterel", fact: "One of New Zealand's rarest shorebirds, with two distinct populations so different in behaviour that they were once considered separate species. The northern population nests on beaches; the southern population nests only on the summit of Stewart Island, a 10 km hike from the coast.", photo: "" },
  { name: "Logrunner", fact: "An Australian rainforest bird that forages by bracing on its stiff spine-tipped tail and using both feet simultaneously to rake leaf litter aside with violent backwards kicks — creating a characteristic rustling sound heard throughout the forest floor. Pairs duet loudly each morning to announce their territory.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/290766843/medium.jpeg" },

  // Europe
  { name: "Bearded Vulture", fact: "Deliberately dyes its white feathers orange-red by bathing in iron-rich mud — the only bird known to intentionally colour itself. It subsists almost entirely on bones, dropping them from heights of up to 80 metres onto rocks to shatter them, then swallowing the fragments whole.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/65759335/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "European Bee-eater", fact: "Catches bees and wasps in the air by sight, then beats them against a branch to discharge the sting and squeezes out the venom sac before swallowing. A single pair can catch 250 bees a day. Pairs are often assisted by 'helpers' — older offspring who forgo breeding to help raise younger siblings.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/70043412/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Common Kingfisher", fact: "Dives into water at up to 40 km/h with eyes closed, judging the fish's refracted position from above the surface. The bill is shaped like an asymmetric wedge — wider at the tip — to enter water without splashing. Engineers studied kingfisher anatomy to redesign the nose of Japan's Shinkansen bullet train.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/61266631/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Atlantic Puffin", fact: "Can carry over 60 fish crosswise in its bill at once — the record is 83. The tongue has backward-pointing spines that pin each fish against the palate, freeing the bill to open and catch more. It digs its nest burrow with its bill, sometimes excavating a metre-long tunnel.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/63139388/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Great Bustard", fact: "The world's heaviest flying bird, with males reaching 21 kg. During courtship the male inflates his neck, fans his tail over his back, and flips his wing feathers inside-out to become an implausible white powder-puff of froth — visible from over a kilometre. Females are less than a third the male's weight.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/529750298/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "White-tailed Eagle", fact: "Europe's largest eagle, with a wingspan of up to 2.4 metres. Extinct in Britain for over a century before reintroduction. It was once believed to steal lambs, leading to extermination campaigns — though it is primarily a fish eagle that also takes waterbirds and carrion.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/164904961/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Eurasian Bittern", fact: "Its booming call — a deep, resonant pulse heard up to 5 km away — is made by inflating the oesophagus as a resonating chamber. When alarmed it freezes with bill pointing straight up, striped neck blending with surrounding reed stems so perfectly that it becomes invisible even in an open reedbed.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/60579218/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Dalmatian Pelican", fact: "The world's largest pelican and one of the heaviest flying birds, weighing up to 15 kg. The curly feathers on its head and the vivid orange-red pouch in breeding condition make it the most striking of all pelicans. Fewer than 12,000 remain, mostly in eastern Europe and Central Asia.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/51559911/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Eurasian Eagle Owl", fact: "One of the world's largest owls, capable of killing deer fawns, foxes and other raptors. Its orange eyes are fixed — it cannot move them in their sockets — so it compensates with a neck that rotates 270 degrees. Pairs hoot as a duet, and can be heard on still nights from 4 km away.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/1840610/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Great Grey Shrike", fact: "A predatory songbird that impales beetles, small mammals and even small birds on thorns or barbed wire — creating a 'larder' to return to later, or to display its hunting prowess to females. The larder's contents also preserve in cold weather, providing food stores through harsh winters.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/137178343/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Wallcreeper", fact: "Creeps up sheer cliff faces with the nimble confidence of a butterfly, constantly flicking its crimson wings in nervous little bursts. It nests on vertical rock faces in the Alps and Himalayas at altitudes above 3,000 metres, descending to lower gorges and old buildings in winter.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/160447350/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Snow Bunting", fact: "One of the most northerly-breeding birds on Earth, nesting in rock crevices on Svalbard and Arctic Greenland where snow can fall in any month. The male arrives on the Arctic breeding grounds up to five weeks before the female, enduring temperatures below -30°C to secure the best territories.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/113763306/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Eurasian Dotterel", fact: "Sex roles are completely reversed: the female is larger and more boldly patterned, arrives on the breeding grounds first, courts the male, then lays the eggs and leaves. The male incubates and raises the chicks entirely alone. Females sometimes mate with multiple males in the same season.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/23655/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Ruff", fact: "Males come in three distinct forms — dark-ruffed 'independents', pale 'satellites' and small female-mimicking 'faeders' — that use completely different mating strategies. Satellites cooperate with independents at leks rather than compete with them, gaining matings through proximity. The female is called a Reeve.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/277856852/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Red Kite", fact: "Has a forked tail it uses like a rudder, banking and wheeling in slow, effortless circles. In medieval London, kites were so numerous they scavenged meat from butchers' stalls and even snatched food from children's hands. Poisoned to extinction in England, then spectacularly reintroduced in the 1990s.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/606105986/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Eurasian Roller", fact: "Named for the male's spectacular tumbling courtship flight, in which he climbs steeply and then rolls and dives while calling loudly. The electric blue of its wings is invisible when perched but explodes into view on takeoff. It nests in holes and is absent from most of its former range due to pesticide use.", photo: "" },
  { name: "Wryneck", fact: "Can twist its head almost 180 degrees like an owl — giving it its name. When caught in the hand it hisses, puffs up and rotates its head in slow spirals, mimicking a snake. Unlike woodpeckers it cannot excavate its own nest, instead taking over natural holes or evicting other species.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/105374707/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Eurasian Spoonbill", fact: "Swings its spatulate bill from side to side through shallow water in a scything motion, snapping shut by touch the instant it contacts a small fish or invertebrate. Chicks hatch with a straight bill that only develops the spoon shape as they grow. They feed through their parents' bill like a chute.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/8809/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Black Woodpecker", fact: "Europe's largest woodpecker, the size of a crow, which hammers dead trees so ferociously it can excavate a hole in minutes. Its excavations open up cavities used by dozens of other forest species including owls, ducks, and flying squirrels. A single tree with a Black Woodpecker hole becomes a hub of forest biodiversity.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/31574109/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Hawfinch", fact: "Has the most powerful bill of any European songbird, capable of crushing cherry stones with a force of up to 70 kg — roughly what you'd feel standing on a scale. The bill's interior is lined with a grooved pad for gripping slippery seeds, and the jaw muscles account for a third of its total body weight.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/188331058/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Penduline Tit", fact: "Builds one of the most intricate nests in Europe: a purse-shaped bag woven from plant fibres and willow down, hung from a thin branch over water with a false entrance as a decoy. The real entrance is a closeable flap. Building takes two weeks and uses up to 10,000 individual fibres.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/606114054/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "White-winged Snowfinch", fact: "Lives year-round at Alpine altitudes above the treeline, often above 2,500 metres, including in deep winter when its habitat is buried under metres of snow. It forages around ski lifts and mountain huts, having learned to exploit human food waste as a winter survival strategy.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/27975599/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Cinereous Vulture", fact: "Europe's and Asia's largest bird of prey, with a wingspan of nearly 3 metres. Unlike most vultures it prefers to eat the dry skin, tendons and ligaments that others ignore, using its massive hooked bill. A single bird can consume 1.5 kg of food in one sitting.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/192396793/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Common Firecrest", fact: "One of Europe's smallest birds at 5–6 grams, but among its most vivid — the male has a dazzling crown of orange, yellow and black stripes. It hovers briefly while gleaning insects from the tips of spruce needles, and can survive sub-zero temperatures by roosting communally and entering daily torpor.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/173469227/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Bluethroat", fact: "The male's throat is a vivid mosaic of blue, orange and white that varies between subspecies. It is one of the finest mimics in Europe, weaving the songs of dozens of other species into its own. It hops on the ground rather than perching and prefers thick cover close to water.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/104155463/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Pygmy Cormorant", fact: "The smallest cormorant in the world, barely larger than a Mallard. It dives in shallow freshwater lakes and rivers, often submerging completely in less than a metre of water. Its feathers are not fully waterproof, so after each diving session it stands with wings spread to dry, like all cormorants.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/48978906/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Eurasian Scops Owl", fact: "A tiny migratory owl that summers in southern Europe and winters in Africa. Its advertising call — a monotonous, repetitive 'toop' repeated for hours — carries up to 800 metres but is so consistent that it is easy to walk past the calling bird without ever pinpointing it.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/32019292/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Tengmalm's Owl", fact: "Nests only in old Black Woodpecker holes in boreal forest. The female sits so tight on eggs that she can be lifted off the nest by hand. The male caches food around the nesting hole, and in good vole years provides so much prey that some food rots before being eaten.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/37067370/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Great Snipe", fact: "Males gather at leks and display at night with rapid bill-snapping, tail-fanning and wing-shivering displays, competing in groups of up to 20. They have been recorded making the fastest unassisted migration flight of any bird — 7,000 km in 59 hours without stopping.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/308401790/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Eurasian Woodcock", fact: "Has eyes set so far back on its head it has a wider field of vision behind it than in front, allowing it to watch for predators while probing soil with its flexible bill tip. Males fly a regular 'roding' patrol circuit at dusk, calling with a peculiar frog-like croak, to claim territory.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/64987854/medium.jpg" },

  // North America
  { name: "Arctic Tern", fact: "Migrates from the Arctic to the Antarctic and back every year — up to 90,000 km round trip. Over a 30-year lifespan it covers the equivalent of three trips to the Moon and back. It sees more daylight than any other creature on Earth, spending both Arctic and Antarctic summers in perpetual sun.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/96821961/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Peregrine Falcon", fact: "The fastest animal on Earth in a hunting stoop, exceeding 390 km/h. It strikes prey with a half-closed fist to avoid breaking its own feet on impact. Special baffles in its nostrils reduce the air pressure entering its lungs — without them, the impact of breathing at that speed would be fatal.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/212499566/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Snowy Owl", fact: "Can pinpoint and plunge into a lemming moving under 30 cm of compacted snow using hearing alone. In boom years for lemmings a pair may raise 11 chicks; in lean years they don't breed at all. Females have more dark markings than males, and fully white individuals are almost always old males.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/150549757/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Greater Roadrunner", fact: "Runs at 32 km/h and regularly kills rattlesnakes by seizing the head and slamming it against a rock. On cold desert mornings it spreads its back feathers to expose a patch of dark skin to the sun, using its own body as a solar panel to rewarm itself before it can function properly.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/128132945/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Clark's Nutcracker", fact: "Caches up to 98,000 pine seeds across hundreds of locations each autumn and can retrieve most of them months later under metres of snow. This spatial memory is so remarkable it has reshaped mountain pine forests — whitebark pines cannot regenerate without the nutcracker replanting their seeds.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/350111806/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Burrowing Owl", fact: "Actively 'farms' food by spreading mammal dung around its burrow entrance to attract dung beetles, then eats the beetles. Inside the burrow, when threatened, it mimics the sound of a rattlesnake — a hissing buzz that predators recognise, deterring them from investigating the hole.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/57747291/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Common Loon", fact: "Its haunting wail carries 10 km across still water. Eyes turn blood-red in breeding season. It is so perfectly adapted for diving — bones nearly solid, feet set far back — that it is almost unable to walk on land, pushing itself along on its belly. It can dive to 60 metres for fish.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/2960972/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Osprey", fact: "The only hawk that dives feet-first into water to catch fish. Its outer toe is reversible, allowing it to grip fish with two toes in front and two behind. It always rotates the fish head-forward before flying — reducing aerodynamic drag. Almost always found near water, on every continent except Antarctica.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/6903515/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Anna's Hummingbird", fact: "During its courtship dive, the male accelerates to 385 body-lengths per second — proportionally the fastest movement ever recorded in a vertebrate. At the bottom of the dive he produces a sharp chirp from his tail feathers, not his syrinx. He can sing through his nose while his throat is puffed up displaying.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/358438292/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Bobolink", fact: "The only North American land bird that is entirely black below and white above — the reverse of almost every other bird. Migrates 20,000 km to Argentina and back, navigating partly by detecting Earth's magnetic field using magnetite crystals in its head. Its bubbling song sounds like R2-D2.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/4836761/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Red Knot", fact: "Migrates from the Arctic to Tierra del Fuego and back — 30,000 km a year — making it one of the longest migrations of any bird relative to body size. Each spring it stops on Delaware Bay to gorge on horseshoe crab eggs, nearly doubling its weight in two weeks before the final push north.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/236294/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Limpkin", fact: "Its screaming wail — described as the sound of someone being murdered in a swamp — was used as the Hippogriff's call in Harry Potter films and features as various monster sounds in Hollywood productions. In reality it is a shy wetland bird that specialises in extracting apple snails with a slightly twisted bill.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/161521395/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Snail Kite", fact: "Has evolved a thin, sharply hooked bill as a single-purpose tool for extracting apple snails from their shells — a technique it performs faster than any other predator. So specialised is it that when apple snail populations crash, snail kites also crash in numbers and their range contracts dramatically.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/3492573/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "American Dipper", fact: "The only truly aquatic songbird in North America. It walks and swims underwater on river bottoms, gripping stones with strong toes while hunting for invertebrates. It has a third eyelid (nictitating membrane) that turns green when submerged, helping it see underwater, and a flap that closes its nostrils when diving.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/247681814/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Harlequin Duck", fact: "Breeds on fast-moving mountain torrents, diving and swimming through rapids where other ducks would be swept away. The male's extraordinary patchwork of slate-blue, chestnut and white — resembling a harlequin costume — is arguably the most complex pattern of any duck.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/172955323/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Painted Bunting", fact: "The male is often called the most colourful bird in North America — cobalt blue head, red underparts, lime-green back — but is so secretive and skulking that many birders spend years trying to see one. Males are so aggressive toward rivals they fight to the death in some cases.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/293862224/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Scissor-tailed Flycatcher", fact: "Its tail — up to 38 cm long — is used as a rudder for the remarkable aerial acrobatics it performs while catching flying insects. During courtship the male performs a roller-coaster flight, zigzagging steeply while flashing his salmon-pink underwing. Oklahoma's state bird.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/8519117/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Long-billed Curlew", fact: "Has North America's longest bill of any shorebird — up to 20 cm — which it plunges deep into mud to reach burrowing crabs and shrimps. The curve matches the curve of ghost crab burrows precisely. When foraging in grasslands it uses the bill to snatch grasshoppers and even small lizards.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/169122861/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Whooping Crane", fact: "North America's tallest bird nearly went extinct, with only 15 individuals remaining in 1941. Through intensive conservation including captive breeding and ultralight-aircraft-led migration training — teaching captive-bred birds their migration route — the population has climbed back above 800.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/25148925/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "California Condor", fact: "With a wingspan of 3 metres, it rides thermals over canyons and coastlines surveying vast areas for carrion. Extinct in the wild in 1987, with just 27 remaining, the entire species was captured for a breeding programme. There are now over 500, including free-flying birds that soar over the Grand Canyon again.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/205288597/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Vermilion Flycatcher", fact: "The male is an implausible combination of vivid scarlet and sooty black, somehow present in dry scrub and deserts. During courtship he catches a butterfly or large insect, carries it in his bill, and performs a slow fluttering 'butterfly flight' over the female — combining a display with a gift.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/166991696/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Phainopepla", fact: "A silky flycatcher of Sonoran Desert that is entirely dependent on desert mistletoe — both eating the berries and dispersing the seeds in its droppings. A single bird eats over 1,000 mistletoe berries a day. It breeds twice a year in completely different habitats: once in the desert, once in cooler oak woodland.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/6478570/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Elf Owl", fact: "The world's lightest owl at 40 grams — smaller than a sparrow. It nests in old woodpecker holes in saguaro cacti. Despite its tiny size it migrates to Mexico for winter. It defends itself by playing dead with convincing floppy limpness when caught, sometimes fooling even experienced handlers.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/45691213/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Elegant Trogon", fact: "Has a striking colour contrast — metallic green above, crimson below — but sits so still in dappled forest shade that it is almost impossible to spot despite its colours. Its call is a low, cooing 'co-ah' that resonates through the canyon. It nests in old woodpecker holes in sycamore trees.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/463590389/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Thick-billed Parrot", fact: "The only parrot currently breeding in the United States — or rather, just across the border in Mexico, making seasonal foraging trips into Arizona's pine forests. It feeds on pine cone seeds, using its thick bill to tear apart cones that other birds cannot open. Extinct in the US, reintroduction attempts are ongoing.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/102436108/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Marbled Murrelet", fact: "Defies the pattern for alcids by nesting not on cliffs but in old-growth forests — sometimes 80 km inland — laying a single egg on a mossy branch. Discovered only in 1974 and the nest so hard to find that its discovery required a tree climber who stumbled upon it by accident in a California redwood.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/22437887/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Western Grebe", fact: "Performs one of the most spectacular courtship displays of any bird: pairs run side-by-side across the water in perfect synchrony at high speed for up to 20 metres without sinking. Called 'rushing', it is triggered by a specific mutual calling sequence and appears impossible to fake to the partner.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/434823221/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Spruce Grouse", fact: "So tame in the boreal forest that it allows humans to approach within arm's length, earning the nickname 'fool hen.' It subsists almost entirely on spruce needles in winter — one of the least nutritious diets imaginable — surviving by having an enlarged, highly acidic gizzard to break down the tough plant matter.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/129917066/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Tufted Puffin", fact: "The dramatic golden head tufts and red-orange bill appear only in breeding season and are shed like a mask in late summer, leaving a plain-faced bird. It can carry dozens of fish in its bill thanks to a rough tongue that pins them while the bill opens for more. It dives up to 60 metres deep.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/158977255/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Rhinoceros Auklet", fact: "Despite its name it's more closely related to puffins. The 'horn' at the base of its bill — visible only in breeding season — has no known function and disappears after nesting. It feeds entirely at night, navigating to its burrow in total darkness and passing fish to its chick without light.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/52927456/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Ivory Gull", fact: "One of the world's most northerly birds, spending its entire life in the High Arctic. Its brilliant white plumage provides camouflage in a world of snow and ice. It follows polar bears to scavenge seal carcasses and has been observed eating polar bear faeces — one of the least fussy diets in the bird world.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/182350159/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Ross's Gull", fact: "An Arctic gull so rarely seen outside the extreme north that a single individual appearing in England in 1975 drew over 100,000 birdwatchers to a small Yorkshire town in what became known as one of birding's greatest twitches. It has a faint pink flush on its white breast that deepens in breeding season.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/195607089/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Steller's Sea Eagle", fact: "The heaviest eagle on Earth at up to 9 kg, with a wingspan over 2.5 metres. Its massive orange-yellow bill is the largest of any eagle. It can carry off a full-grown Pacific salmon and dominates every other raptor at carcasses, including other eagle species.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/402669764/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Bristle-thighed Curlew", fact: "The only shorebird known to use tools: it picks up pebbles or twigs and uses them to crack open seabird eggs on Pacific atolls, providing a food source no other shorebird can access. The only shorebird to winter on remote Pacific islands rather than continental coasts or estuaries.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/64845049/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Kirtland's Warbler", fact: "Nests only in young jack pine forests in a single county in Michigan and requires trees of exactly the right age — too young or too old and it abandons the habitat. Its population collapsed to 167 singing males in 1974 before intensive management of forest age and cowbird control brought it back above 2,000.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/525790554/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Prothonotary Warbler", fact: "Named for the golden-yellow robes worn by papal notaries — the only eastern wood warbler to nest in tree cavities rather than open cup nests. It nests so close to water that it sometimes places its nest inside a hollow stump that floods periodically, raising young centimetres above the rising water.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/456591408/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Gunnison Sage-Grouse", fact: "Discovered as a new species as recently as 2000, hidden in plain sight in Colorado. Males inflate two yellow air sacs in their chest and fan their spiked tail into a starburst during display — but the Gunnison's display is distinctly more flamboyant than its close relative, with more exaggerated tail plumes.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/18100968/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Roseate Spoonbill", fact: "Gets its shocking pink colour from carotenoid pigments in the shrimp and other crustaceans it eats — the same source as flamingo pink. It sweeps its spatula-shaped bill side to side through shallow water, snapping shut by touch. Young birds are white, slowly turning pink as they eat more shrimp.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/32776247/medium.jpg" },

  // Central America & Caribbean
  { name: "Resplendent Quetzal", fact: "Sacred to the ancient Maya and Aztec as a living symbol of freedom — reportedly it died if captured. The male's iridescent tail streamers exceed 60 cm, nearly three times its body length. Guatemala's currency is named after it, and it appears on the national flag.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/177163816/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Turquoise-browed Motmot", fact: "The national bird of both El Salvador and Nicaragua. It wags its racket-tipped tail like a pendulum, and researchers believe this signals to predators that it has spotted them — advertising its alertness as a deterrent. It creates the bare tail shaft itself, preening off the barbs as the feather grows.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/32798954/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Keel-billed Toucan", fact: "Its enormous bill is roughly a third of its total body length but weighs almost nothing — it is hollow keratin over a spongy bone lattice. The toucan uses it to reach fruit on thin branch tips too fragile to land on, and as a radiator: blood flow through the bill regulates body temperature in the heat.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/2964195/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Harpy Eagle", fact: "The most powerful eagle in the Americas, with talons the size of a grizzly bear's claws. It hunts sloths, monkeys and large iguanas through the forest canopy at speed. Pairs raise a single chick every two to three years. Indigenous Amazonian people regard it as a god of the sky.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/447085421/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Sunbittern", fact: "Appears to be a dull brown wading bird — until it suddenly spreads its wings to reveal two huge eye-like patterns. The display is so startling it has been known to make humans stumble backwards. The 'eyes' may mimic an owl or large predator, confusing a threat long enough for the bird to escape.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/28961736/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Bee Hummingbird", fact: "The world's smallest living bird — just 5 cm long and weighing 1.6 grams, roughly the size of a bumblebee. Its eggs are the size of a pea. Heart rate reaches 1,200 beats per minute and wings beat 80 times per second. Found only in Cuba.", photo: "" },
  { name: "Wire-tailed Manakin", fact: "The male has two tail feathers that narrow to bare wire filaments tipped with tiny balls, which he trails along the female's chin during the final phase of courtship — a physical interaction so intimate that it seems to function as a tactile assessment of male quality.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/269174478/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Club-winged Manakin", fact: "The only bird known to produce sound with its wings by using one feather as a pick and another as a washboard — vibrating them together at 107 times per second to produce a clear musical tone. To support this, its wing bones are twice as dense as those of other birds of the same size.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/135738734/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Amazonian Umbrellabird", fact: "The male has a huge erectile crest that unfurls over his bill like a black umbrella, and a long inflatable wattle hanging from his chest covered in scale-like feathers. He boom-calls from a display perch in the forest subcanopy, with the wattle amplifying the sound like a megaphone.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/10396859/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Spectacled Owl", fact: "Has white 'spectacle' markings framing its dark facial disc in reverse — dark face, white rings — making it look like it's wearing glasses the wrong way. Unlike most owls it inhabits dense tropical forest and is rarely seen despite being one of the largest owls in the Americas.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/226401151/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Sungrebe", fact: "The male carries newly hatched chicks in pouches of skin under each wing and can fly with them if threatened — the only bird that flies with young concealed on its body. Chicks develop in the pouch while still at an almost embryonic stage, completing their development in flight.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/256286343/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Agami Heron", fact: "One of the most spectacular herons in the world and one of the hardest to see — it hunts alone in deep shade along tiny forest streams, standing absolutely motionless for long periods before striking at fish with a lightning-fast spear. The male develops extraordinary plumes of blue, chestnut and white in breeding season.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/11731497/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Zigzag Heron", fact: "Tiny, barely 30 cm tall, with bold zigzag black-and-buff streaking that makes it virtually invisible among dry reeds. So secretive and rarely encountered that basic facts about its breeding and population are still unknown. Found only along forested streams in the Amazon basin.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/160446861/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Snowcap", fact: "One of the most striking hummingbirds in the world: the male is deep iridescent purple with a brilliant white cap, as though someone tipped a pot of white paint on his head. Barely 6 cm long, it is a subordinate species that must feed at flowers after dominant hummingbirds have left.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/347532729/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Royal Flycatcher", fact: "Appears to be a plain brown flycatcher — until it fans its crest into an extraordinary circular sunburst of red, orange and blue, fringed with black spots. The crest is rarely erected except when handled, during courtship, or after a territorial dispute. It looks like a completely different species.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/5864947/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Purple-crowned Fairy", fact: "A large hummingbird with a gleaming white underside and a crown that shifts between vivid violet-purple and deep blue depending on the angle of light. It specialises in piercing the base of long tubular flowers to steal nectar — taking the calories without providing pollination in return.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/449681805/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Fiery-throated Hummingbird", fact: "Appears a dull green from most angles but in direct sun explodes into a mosaic of violet, blue, gold and orange-red at the throat — each patch created by a different nanostructure, visible only from exact angles. Found only in Costa Rica and Panama's highlands above 2,000 metres.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/106942766/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Great Curassow", fact: "A large, turkey-sized bird of Central American rainforest canopy that builds its nest in trees and produces precocial chicks that can fly within days of hatching — almost unique among large birds. The male has a curly black crest and a vivid yellow 'knob' at the base of its bill.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/44656976/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Lovely Cotinga", fact: "The male is a saturated turquoise-blue with a deep purple throat patch — colours produced entirely by light interference in the feather structure rather than pigment, making the blue shift and flash with movement. Found in forest canopy in Central America and northern South America.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/3451116/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Snowy Cotinga", fact: "The male is pure cloud-white with pale blue wing patches and a small dark eye. It inhabits the high canopy of humid forest in Central America, where it is almost invisible against bright sky. Despite being white it is rarely seen — it sits still for hours at a time at the tops of tall trees.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/110921820/medium.jpeg" },

  // South America
  { name: "Andean Condor", fact: "Has the largest wingspan of any land bird — up to 3.3 metres — and can soar for hours without a single wingbeat, rising on Andean thermals. It can go four or five days between meals, then eat up to 5 kg in a single sitting. Males have a large caruncle and bare red facial skin that darkens with mood.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/74741181/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Hoatzin", fact: "Chicks hatch with small claws on their wings, used to scramble through riverbank vegetation — a throwback to early bird evolution not seen in other modern species. Adults smell strongly of fermented plant matter, earning the nickname 'stinkbird.' Its digestive system ferments food like a cow's, not a bird's.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/335722298/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Cock-of-the-rock", fact: "The male is a vivid orange-red disc with a permanent semicircular crest that completely hides his bill. Males gather in 'leks' and perform frenzied hops and bows for silent females. The female is brown and does all the nest-building and chick-rearing herself in a clay cup stuck to a cliff face.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/112436506/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Horned Screamer", fact: "Grows a thin 15 cm spike of cartilage from its forehead — a 'horn' with no known function. It also has sharp bony spurs on each wing used in fights. Despite looking fearsome it is largely herbivorous, and its loud honking call carries for kilometres over South American wetlands.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/182458133/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Jabiru", fact: "The tallest flying bird in the Americas at up to 1.4 metres. In Portuguese, its name means 'swollen neck' — the male's bare neck pouch turns vivid scarlet when aroused or agitated and hangs loose when relaxed. It builds one of the largest nests of any bird, up to 2 metres across.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/263745861/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Inca Tern", fact: "Has a spectacular white moustache of curling feathers, a slate-grey body and a scarlet bill — looking like a tiny, immaculate bandleader. The length of the moustache correlates with health and is used by both sexes to assess potential mates. Found only along the cold Humboldt Current off Peru and Chile.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/143658416/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Emperor Penguin", fact: "Males fast for four months in the Antarctic winter, standing in blizzards at -60°C, holding eggs on their feet in huddles that rotate continuously to share warmth. They lose half their body weight before the chick hatches. They are the deepest-diving birds on Earth, reaching 535 metres.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/7229/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Rockhopper Penguin", fact: "Named for its habit of jumping between boulders on rugged subantarctic islands rather than waddling like other penguins. It has vivid yellow and black head plumes and red eyes, giving it a permanently furious expression. Its harsh, braying call sounds less like a bird than an angry donkey.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/112102893/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Macaroni Penguin", fact: "Named by 18th-century sailors after 'macaroni' — fashionable young men who wore exuberant feathered hats. The golden-orange crest plumes erupt from the forehead like a fountain. With over 18 million individuals, it is the most numerous penguin species on Earth.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/2608962/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Magellanic Penguin", fact: "Migrates up to 3,000 km from Patagonia to Brazil and back each year — one of the longest penguin migrations. Pairs reunite at the same burrow each season and recognise each other by call after months at sea. Males arrive first and wait for their mate, sometimes for weeks.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/345378562/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Torrent Duck", fact: "Lives only on fast-flowing Andean rivers, diving and swimming through rapids that would kill most waterbirds. Males have a vivid red bill and bold black-and-white striping. Pairs hold linear territories along kilometre-long stretches of river and aggressively chase intruders downstream.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/150796384/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Oilbird", fact: "The only nocturnal fruit-eating bird in the world, navigating dark caves by echolocation — the only bird to use sonar habitually. It roosts and breeds in pitch-black caves in colonies of thousands. Chicks gorge on oil palm fruit and grow so fat they weigh more than their parents before fledging.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/336943558/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Capuchinbird", fact: "The male's extraordinary call sounds exactly like a chainsaw revving up — a deep mechanical grinding produced by inflating air sacs and vibrating modified feathers. Males gather in leks and buzz at each other, each trying to out-chainsaw the others. The brown-cowled head inspired the 'capuchin' name.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/269174344/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Purple-breasted Cotinga", fact: "The male is a saturated turquoise-blue with a deep wine-purple breast patch — colours produced entirely by feather nanostructure rather than pigment, making them shift and glow in sunlight. It inhabits high canopy in Amazonia and is rarely seen, spending most of its time motionless at the top of tall trees.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/114350724/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Banded Cotinga", fact: "The male is iridescent blue with a broad violet breast band — among the most vivid birds in the Amazon. Despite its spectacular colours it is rarely encountered because it sits motionless for long periods in the high forest canopy and travels long distances between fruiting trees.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/329233337/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Long-wattled Umbrellabird", fact: "The male has a magnificent umbrella-shaped crest and a long wattle — a pendant of black feathers hanging 35 cm from his chest — which he inflates during display to amplify his low booming call. He performs solo, not in leks, calling from a display perch in the same spot year after year.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/104818772/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Common Potoo", fact: "By day it roosts upright on a broken branch stub, bill raised, eyes slitted, looking indistinguishable from the wood itself. At night it hunts insects by making long sallies from its perch. Its call — a descending series of mournful notes — is one of the most haunting sounds of the Neotropical forest at night.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/508102028/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Great Potoo", fact: "Larger and even more uncanny than the Common Potoo, with huge yellow eyes that can peer through slits even while they appear fully closed. It hunts large moths and bats with spectacular aerial sallies from its perch. The single chick is raised on the same branch stub as the parent, using the same camouflage.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/330965272/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Pale-winged Trumpeter", fact: "Walks through Amazonian forest in noisy groups, producing a low, resonant 'trumpeting' boom using throat air sacs. It is highly social and group members groom each other and sleep in a pile. Despite having wings, it rarely flies and prefers to run from danger. Groups have helpers that assist the breeding pair.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/40771508/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Giant Antpitta", fact: "Despite being the size of a small chicken, this ground bird of Andean cloud forest was so rarely seen that researchers assumed it must be extraordinarily rare — until a guide in Ecuador discovered that individuals could be tamed with earthworms and would walk up to people. 'Maria' became the most photographed antpitta in the world.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/336941653/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Coppery-chested Jacamar", fact: "A small but jewel-like bird of Andean foothills whose copper-green and rufous plumage shimmers in forest light. Like a kingfisher of the forest, it sits motionless on a perch then darts out to snatch butterflies and dragonflies from the air, returning to hammer them against a branch before swallowing.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/34358556/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Rufescent Tiger Heron", fact: "A densely barred, tiger-striped heron of Amazonian rivers that stands motionless in bankside vegetation waiting for fish. Immature birds are even more heavily barred than adults, making them almost invisible in reeds. When threatened it stretches its neck straight up and sways, mimicking a reed in the wind.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/21359/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Titicaca Grebe", fact: "Found only on Lake Titicaca on the Peru-Bolivia border at 3,800 metres — the world's highest large lake. It cannot fly: its wings have reduced to useless stubs over millennia of island life. Populations have fallen sharply due to fishing nets, introduced trout, and water pollution from lakeside cities.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/55778292/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "James's Flamingo", fact: "One of the rarest flamingos, with just 60,000–70,000 individuals. It breeds on remote, highly alkaline salt lakes in the Andes at over 4,000 metres where temperatures fall below freezing nightly. The lake chemistry is so caustic that other birds cannot survive, leaving the flamingos almost no predators.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/79863611/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Puna Flamingo", fact: "Breeds on high-altitude Andean salt lakes alongside James's Flamingo, but can be distinguished by its paler colour and larger size. It commutes hundreds of kilometres between feeding and nesting lakes. Like all flamingos, it eats by filtering algae and invertebrates through a specially adapted upside-down bill.", photo: "" },
  { name: "Hooded Grebe", fact: "Discovered only in 1974 on remote Patagonian lakes, with a population that has since collapsed to perhaps 700 birds. It performs an extraordinary courtship 'ballet' in which pairs rise and run across the water in perfect synchrony — one of the most complex grebe displays known.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/238173998/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Giant Coot", fact: "The heaviest coot in the world, weighing up to 3 kg. Pairs build enormous floating nests up to 3 metres across from aquatic vegetation heaped on the surface of Andean lakes. The nest is so large that other bird species sometimes nest on top of it uninvited.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/42661316/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Wattled Curassow", fact: "A large black forest bird of the western Amazon whose male has a vivid red knob on his bill base and bright crimson facial skin. It is hunted heavily for food and its entire population may number fewer than 10,000. Its booming call resonates through the forest understorey.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/112439100/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Maguari Stork", fact: "A large stork of South American grasslands and wetlands that is one of the few storks to breed in the Southern Hemisphere. Unlike most storks it has a partly reversed hind toe. Males clatter their bills loudly during greeting, throwing their heads back and forward in an exuberant display.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/95770203/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Toco Toucan", fact: "Has the largest bill relative to body size of any bird — up to 20 cm long, accounting for a third of the bird's total length. The bill acts as a thermoregulator, shunting blood to lose heat in the tropics. It sleeps with its bill tucked back over its shoulder to minimise heat loss at night.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/63281117/medium.jpg" },

  // Seabirds & Polar
  { name: "Wandering Albatross", fact: "Has the largest wingspan of any living bird — up to 3.5 metres. It can glide for hundreds of kilometres without a single wingbeat, exploiting the boundary between wind and sea surface in a technique called dynamic soaring. A single bird can circumnavigate the globe in 46 days, covering 120,000 km a year.", photo: "" },
  { name: "Waved Albatross", fact: "Breeds only on the Galápagos island of Española and dances with a partner it will keep for life — bill-clapping, sky-pointing and waddling in rituals that can last hours. It takes 6 years to find a mate, after which pairs return to the same nesting spot year after year.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/46583649/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Light-mantled Albatross", fact: "Often considered the most beautiful albatross — a subtle gradient of ash-grey on its back and white below, with a narrow white eye crescent. It hunts at night, diving to over 5 metres to catch squid. Pairs sing a long duet from the clifftop, their synchronised calls audible across the nesting colony.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/137288583/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Southern Giant Petrel", fact: "The vulture of the Southern Ocean — it feeds on penguin and seal carcasses, plunging its whole head inside the body cavity, and intimidates other seabirds at carrion. It also hunts live prey, killing petrels and prions at sea. Breeding birds develop a huge hook-tipped bill stained permanently red-brown from blood.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/112193825/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Snow Petrel", fact: "Pure white except for a black bill and eye, it nests further south than any other bird — deep in Antarctic mountain valleys hundreds of kilometres from open water. It has been found breeding at 440 km from the sea. Its stomach oil, used to feed chicks and repel predators, smells so powerfully it can be detected from metres away.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/175847822/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Blue-footed Booby", fact: "The male's blue feet are a direct measure of health — fed by carotenoids from fresh fish. Females actively prefer males with the brightest blue feet and will abandon a nest if a male's feet fade. Males advertise their feet by stepping exaggeratedly in a 'high-stepping' dance toward females.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/225718/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Red-footed Booby", fact: "The only booby that nests in trees rather than on the ground. It has a prehensile grip in its feet for clinging to branches in high winds, and red feet that flush darker during courtship. There are two colour morphs — white and brown — that breed together in the same colonies.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/381898061/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Magnificent Frigatebird", fact: "Males inflate a bright red throat pouch to the size of a football to attract females circling overhead. The pouch is inflated for up to 20 minutes and produces a rhythmic drumming sound. Frigatebirds cannot land on water — their feathers are not waterproof — so they steal fish mid-air from other seabirds.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/176818863/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "White Tern", fact: "Lays a single egg balanced directly on a bare branch with no nest material whatsoever — the most precarious nesting strategy of any bird. Chicks hatch with especially long, strong toes for gripping, and have been shown to tilt the egg against the wind to stop it rolling off. Also called the Fairy Tern.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/59723819/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "South Polar Skua", fact: "Breeds within metres of the geographic South Pole — the most southerly nesting bird on Earth. It aggressively attacks anything near its nest, including humans, striking the back of the head hard enough to draw blood. Pairs sometimes fly thousands of kilometres to the North Atlantic between breeding seasons.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/177423932/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Long-tailed Jaeger", fact: "The most elegant of the jaegers, with tail streamers up to 23 cm that flutter behind it in effortless, buoyant flight. On the Arctic breeding grounds it hunts lemmings like a falcon; at sea it becomes a pirate, chasing terns and other small seabirds until they drop their catch.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/607915441/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Swallow-tailed Gull", fact: "The world's only fully nocturnal gull — it hunts squid at night using unusually large eyes and hunts entirely at sea during the non-breeding season. It nests on the Galápagos and has red eye-rings that may help signal its nocturnal lifestyle to its partner.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/228214/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Sooty Shearwater", fact: "Undertakes one of the longest migrations ever recorded — over 65,000 km in a figure-eight loop from New Zealand to the North Pacific and back, taking advantage of prevailing winds in each hemisphere. Millions were once harvested as 'muttonbirds' by Māori in New Zealand.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/342192558/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Manx Shearwater", fact: "A seabird so perfectly adapted to ocean life that it is helpless on land, shuffling on its elbows. It navigates to its burrow on a dark Welsh island from thousands of kilometres away, arriving in absolute darkness. One individual ringed in 1953 was still breeding in 2003 — at least 55 years old.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/203014909/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Wilson's Storm Petrel", fact: "One of the most abundant birds on Earth, with a population estimated in the tens of millions. It is barely the size of a sparrow, yet spends its entire life at sea except when nesting in Antarctica. It 'walks' on the water surface with dangling feet while pattering with its wings — apparently feeding on plankton.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/220518955/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Red-billed Tropicbird", fact: "Has two brilliant red central tail feathers up to 40 cm long that trail behind it like streamers. It flies with rapid, stiff wingbeats that look mechanical compared to other seabirds. Fights over nest sites are violent: tropicbirds plunge into their competitors and beat them with their wings in mid-air.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/437472712/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "White-tailed Tropicbird", fact: "The only tropicbird with yellow or orange bill. Its two white tail streamers flutter in the wind as it soars over tropical oceans. It is among the few seabirds to breed on the Atlantic island of Bermuda, where it is considered a cultural symbol and known locally as the 'longtail.'", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/201864305/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Abbott's Booby", fact: "Breeds only on Christmas Island in the Indian Ocean and is the most ancient living booby species. Pairs take over two years to raise a single chick. So slow is its breeding that even a relatively small number of nest failures each year can cause the population — already fewer than 6,000 pairs — to decline.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/172749543/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Masked Booby", fact: "The largest booby, with a white body and stark black mask and wing tips. It lays two eggs but almost always raises only one chick: the older sibling ejects the younger one from the nest within days of hatching in an act of obligate siblicide that has been observed consistently across the species.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/214608110/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Brown Noddy", fact: "Builds a nest of seaweed and feathers on coral rocks or in shrubs, often returning to the same site for years, cementing new material on top until the nest becomes a substantial structure. It nods its head vigorously during courtship — hence the name — while calling with a deep crow-like croak.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/6579420/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Christmas Frigatebird", fact: "Breeds only on Christmas Island in the Indian Ocean. The male inflates his scarlet throat pouch and rattles his bill against it to produce a drumming sound audible across the colony. With only about 3,000 pairs remaining, it is one of the most endangered seabirds in the Indo-Pacific.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/8745635/medium.jpg" },

  // Owls & Nightbirds
  { name: "Great Grey Owl", fact: "Can hear a mouse moving under 60 cm of packed snow from 100 metres away, and plunges face-first through the crust to catch prey it never sees. Despite its impressive size it is mostly feathers — its body mass is less than that of a Great Horned Owl. Its facial disc acts as a parabolic sound collector.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/179795514/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Blakiston's Fish Owl", fact: "The world's largest owl, weighing up to 4.5 kg and with a wingspan approaching 2 metres. It hunts fish by wading into shallow rivers in Russia and Japan, snatching them with its talons. Pairs are devoted, using the same territory for decades. It calls as a deep, resonant duet in the frozen forest at night.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/65762028/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Verreaux's Eagle Owl", fact: "Africa's largest owl, with vivid pink eyelids — unique among owls — and deep brown eyes. It hunts hedgehogs, spring hares and even other raptors. The male provides all food to the female during incubation. Its low booming call carries across African bushveld on still nights.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/1865389/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Crested Owl", fact: "A medium-sized owl of Central and South American forests with extraordinarily long white eyebrows that erupt like bushy horns — giving it a permanently astonished expression. It roosts by day in dense vine tangles and is rarely seen. Almost nothing is known about its breeding behaviour in the wild.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/175632579/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Long-eared Owl", fact: "The 'ears' are not ears but tufts of feathers that function as camouflage — mimicking broken branch stubs — and are used to signal mood. It hunts by hearing alone in darkness, its asymmetric skull placing the ears at different heights to triangulate sound in three dimensions. It roosts communally in winter, sometimes in groups of 50.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/133553640/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Barn Owl", fact: "Has the most sensitive hearing of any animal ever tested. The heart-shaped facial disc funnels sound to asymmetrically placed ears — one higher than the other — allowing it to pinpoint a mouse in total darkness. It swallows prey whole and regurgitates compacted pellets of bone and fur.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/103695544/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Papuan Frogmouth", fact: "A large nocturnal bird of New Guinea that resembles a massive grey tree stump by day, sitting motionless with its mouth slightly agape. At night it hunts large insects and small vertebrates by pouncing from a perch. Its call is a deep, hollow booming that reverberates through the forest.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/66449554/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Standard-winged Nightjar", fact: "The breeding male grows one primary feather on each wing to twice the wing length, with the barbs only at the tip — creating two enormous pennant flags that trail behind him in slow, fluttering display flights over the African bush at dusk. After breeding he moults them off and looks like an ordinary nightjar.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/5461443/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Lyre-tailed Nightjar", fact: "Has outer tail feathers shaped like a lyre — curving outward at the base then inward at the tip — used in aerial display. Found in the rainforests of West Africa and so poorly known that details of its breeding, population and distribution remain incompletely documented by ornithologists.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/23496139/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Pharaoh Eagle Owl", fact: "The desert equivalent of the Eurasian Eagle Owl — slightly smaller, paler and adapted to hot, arid landscapes across North Africa and the Middle East. It nests on cliff ledges and in rocky gullies with no cover, and hunts desert hares, large lizards and gerbils across enormous territories.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/17703/medium.jpg" },

];

// ── Hard-mode bird pool ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
// Compound hyphenated names that match the SNEAKY fake-name generator style.
const HARD_BIRDS = [
  { name: "Yellow-rumped Warbler", fact: "The most numerous warbler in North America, with a talent shared by almost no other warbler: it can digest the waxy coating of bayberries and myrtle berries, allowing it to winter far north of other species. The rump patch is so diagnostic that birders simply call it 'butter butt.'", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/128439522/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Black-crowned Night Heron", fact: "Found on every continent except Australia and Antarctica — the most widespread heron species on Earth. It hunts at dusk and through the night, and its stomach acids are powerful enough to dissolve fish bones entirely. By day it roosts in groups, sometimes in city parks, looking hunched and sullen.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/49357930/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Red-tailed Hawk", fact: "The most common hawk in North America. Despite being genuinely common, its scream is almost never heard in nature — Hollywood has used it as the generic 'hawk or eagle' sound effect for every raptor on screen for decades. The brick-red tail only develops in the second year of life.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/101327658/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "White-throated Sparrow", fact: "Comes in two colour forms — tan-striped and white-striped — that almost always mate with the opposite form. The two morphs are genetically distinct, differ in personality and behaviour, and researchers consider them effectively four sexes: two morphs each in male and female.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/23268661/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Blue-winged Teal", fact: "One of the earliest-departing ducks each autumn, leaving for South America weeks before other species. It can apparently detect the pressure drop that precedes an oncoming storm and begins its southward migration immediately, sometimes travelling through the night to stay ahead of it.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/286292345/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Golden-fronted Woodpecker", fact: "A colourful woodpecker of Texas and Central America whose golden nape and red crown flash brilliantly in sunlight. Unlike many woodpeckers it prefers cacti and mesquite to forest trees, drilling into dry wood for insects and storing acorns in crevices across its arid-scrub territory.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/248378790/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Red-breasted Nuthatch", fact: "Paints sticky conifer resin around the entrance of its nest hole, possibly as a barrier to predators and parasites. It applies the resin with a piece of bark held in its bill, carefully avoiding the glue itself, and renews it throughout the breeding season. It is also one of the most irruptive birds — appearing in vast numbers some winters, almost absent the next.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/117331702/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Yellow-bellied Sapsucker", fact: "Drills precise rows of small holes in tree bark and returns repeatedly to lap up the oozing sap and trapped insects. At least 35 other bird species — including hummingbirds that overwinter because of it — depend on sapsucker wells as a food source. It is the only woodpecker in eastern North America that is fully migratory.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/294094189/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Golden-crowned Kinglet", fact: "One of North America's smallest birds at just 6 grams — barely the weight of a sheet of paper. It survives northern winters at -40°C by huddling in groups and shivering continuously through the night to maintain body temperature, consuming half its weight in insects each day to fuel it.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/59391481/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Black-bellied Plover", fact: "Has a hidden fourth hind toe that other plovers lack. Its plumage transforms completely between seasons — jet black below in summer, pale grey in winter — making it look like two entirely different species. It uses a wider range of habitats than almost any other shorebird, from Arctic tundra to tropical beaches.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/10603462/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "White-crowned Sparrow", fact: "Has distinct regional dialects: a bird from San Francisco sings a song its cousins in Alaska would not recognise. Young males learn the local dialect within weeks of hatching and sing it for life, even if moved. The dialect boundary can be mapped precisely, sometimes to a street or ridgeline.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/27928/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Chestnut-backed Chickadee", fact: "Hides thousands of individual seeds in separate locations each autumn and can find most of them months later under deep snow. Its hippocampus — the brain's memory centre — measurably enlarges each autumn as it begins caching and shrinks again in spring when memory demand drops.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/57455544/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Rufous-tailed Hummingbird", fact: "The commonest hummingbird in Central America, visiting over 150 plant species and acting as primary pollinator for dozens of them. Males defend flowering trees so fiercely they routinely chase away birds ten times their size, including kestrels and kites — and will chase a human hand reaching toward the feeder.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/471912081/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Black-backed Woodpecker", fact: "Specialises in freshly burned boreal forest, arriving within months of a wildfire and apparently able to detect smoke from dozens of kilometres away. Its sooty black back camouflages it perfectly against charred tree trunks. It excavates nesting cavities in fire-killed wood that would be too hard for most woodpeckers to breach.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/419064489/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Olive-backed Sunbird", fact: "A tiny nectar-feeding bird of Southeast Asia and Australasia that hovers like a hummingbird but prefers to perch while feeding. The male's throat is a blaze of metallic purple and yellow visible only in direct sunlight; in shade he looks plain. Its nest is a beautifully woven hanging pouch.", photo: "" },
  { name: "White-bellied Sea Eagle", fact: "Australia and Southeast Asia's second-largest eagle, hunting fish, sea snakes and waterbirds by swooping low over water and snatching prey without getting wet. Pairs mate for life, reusing and expanding the same enormous nest for decades until it can weigh over a tonne.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/368682897/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Rufous-crowned Sparrow", fact: "A desert specialist of rocky hillsides in the American Southwest that rarely drinks free water, extracting all the moisture it needs from insects and seeds. It walks rather than hops, creeping mouse-like between boulders, and is easily overlooked despite having a distinctive rufous crown.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/14283362/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Yellow-billed Oxpecker", fact: "Rides large African mammals eating ticks and parasites — but also keeps wounds open to drink blood, making it partly parasitic on the very animals it appears to help. Buffalo and wildebeest tolerate it; elephants and rhinos often do not and shake it off aggressively.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/35664926/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Blue-naped Mousebird", fact: "Hangs upside down like a bat to roost, packing into tight clusters of up to 20 birds to conserve warmth. On cold mornings it basks belly-to-the-sun with wings spread — a bird in the unusual position of having to warm up before it can fly effectively.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/260366264/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Chestnut-sided Warbler", fact: "One of the few bird species to have genuinely benefited from forest clearance — it barely existed in Audubon's time but thrived as settlers cleared eastern North American forests. Males sing two distinct song types: one to attract females and a quieter one to warn rival males.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/131621127/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Red-faced Cormorant", fact: "Found only in the Aleutian Islands and Kamchatka coast — one of the world's rarest cormorants. The vivid red bare facial skin and blue throat pouch are only present in breeding season, fading to dull brown for the rest of the year, making seasonal identification surprisingly difficult.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/160241870/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "White-winged Crossbill", fact: "Its crossed bill is a precision instrument for prying open spruce cones: it inserts the tip, twists, and flicks out the seed in a fraction of a second. It wanders nomadically across northern forests following cone crops, irrupting into southern regions when spruce crops fail in the north.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/353039022/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Black-headed Grosbeak", fact: "One of the very few birds that can eat monarch butterflies despite their milkweed toxins. It appears to tolerate the cardiac glycosides by feeding in short bouts interspersed with other foods, preventing the poisons from accumulating. It visits monarch overwintering sites in Mexico specifically to exploit this food source.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/390443967/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Yellow-fronted Canary", fact: "Native to sub-Saharan Africa but now established as a feral population in Hawaii after cage-bird escapes. Males can mimic the songs of other species mid-performance, seamlessly stitching foreign phrases into their own song. Captive birds have been trained to hold vocal parts of a human tune.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/161711749/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Rufous-bellied Niltava", fact: "A Himalayan forest flycatcher whose male is a combination of deep cobalt blue above and deep rufous-orange below — a colour scheme so intense that early naturalists considered it one of the most beautiful birds in Asia. Found in montane forests from Nepal to southwest China.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/89407123/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Purple-backed Thornbill", fact: "A tiny high-altitude hummingbird of the Andes whose purple back iridescence flashes brilliantly in sunlight and disappears in shade. Like most thornbills it has a short straight bill and feeds on short tubular flowers, often piercing the base of longer flowers to steal nectar without pollinating them.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/109786470/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Blue-faced Honeyeater", fact: "Has a striking patch of bare blue skin surrounding the eye — vivid turquoise in adults, dull green in juveniles. Young birds from previous years often help their parents raise subsequent broods. It aggressively investigates anything novel in its territory, including people, which makes it easy to observe.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/149111364/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Red-necked Phalarope", fact: "Sex roles are completely reversed: the female is more brightly coloured, courts the male and lays the eggs, then leaves. The male incubates alone and raises the chicks. At sea, phalaropes spin in tight circles to create an upwelling that brings invertebrates to the surface — then snap them up.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/438438392/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "White-cheeked Pintail", fact: "A Caribbean and South American duck with a distinctive white cheek and red bill. Unlike most ducks it grazes on seagrass in saltwater lagoons and mangrove areas as well as freshwater wetlands. It does not form large flocks and is often found in pairs year-round.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/173806806/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Tawny-flanked Prinia", fact: "One of Africa's most abundant and widespread warblers, yet frequently overlooked because of its dull streaky-brown plumage. It pumps its long tail up and down almost constantly, and its scolding alarm call — a sharp repetitive 'prrt-prrt' — is one of the most persistent background sounds in African scrub.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/1927431/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Golden-backed Weaver", fact: "A strikingly patterned weaver of sub-Saharan Africa — golden back, black mask, chestnut underparts — that weaves an intricate oval nest of grass strips suspended from a branch. Males are polygynous, building multiple nests per season; females inspect the construction quality before accepting a mate.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/59339940/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Black-winged Stilt", fact: "Has the longest legs relative to body size of any bird except the flamingo — giving it a perpetually offended, knock-kneed posture. It can wade into water up to its belly with ease, reaching food that other waders can't access. It swims readily when necessary, which stilts rarely need to do.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/20455456/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Buff-fronted Owl", fact: "A small, poorly known owl of montane South America with a warm buff forehead and eyebrows. Despite occupying a range from Venezuela to Argentina, it is so rarely encountered that its diet, breeding biology and vocalizations were largely undescribed until the late 20th century.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/61739943/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Yellow-throated Longclaw", fact: "One of Africa's most vivid grassland birds — bright yellow below with a black chest band — convergent in appearance with the unrelated meadowlarks of North America. Despite the similar look, the two groups are completely unrelated, having evolved the same colours independently in similar habitats.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/2449787/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "White-headed Vulture", fact: "Unusual among African vultures for arriving early and alone at carcasses and actively hunting small animals rather than relying entirely on scavenging. The female's bill base is vivid pink, the male's pale blue. Its population has declined catastrophically due to poisoning of carcasses by poachers.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/43752/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Red-chested Swallow", fact: "A strikingly handsome swallow of sub-Saharan Africa with a deep rufous-red chest band. It associates with large rivers and lakes and often nests inside culverts and under bridges, attaching its mud cup to the underside of concrete overhangs. It migrates within Africa following rainfall.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/5864821/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Blue-spotted Wood Dove", fact: "A tiny dove of African forest floors with iridescent blue wing spots that flash in the dim understorey light. It walks softly through leaf litter like a mouse, head bobbing. Its call is a very soft, descending 'coo-coo-coo' that barely carries, making it far more often heard than seen.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/425390285/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Pale-billed Woodpecker", fact: "One of the largest woodpeckers in Central and South America, with a distinctive pale ivory bill and brilliant red crest. It hammers dead trees with such force that the blows are audible from 400 metres. Its excavations create cavities used by toucans, parrots and large owls.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/172564356/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Black-throated Mango", fact: "A large, bold hummingbird of South America with a gleaming black throat stripe down the centre of its iridescent green body. Males are aggressive and conspicuous, chasing other hummingbirds from flowering trees; females are white below with the black throat reduced to a single central streak.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/219766479/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "White-tipped Dove", fact: "One of the most abundant and widespread doves in Latin America, found from Texas to Argentina in almost any habitat with trees. Its deep, resonant 'coo' is one of the defining sounds of Neotropical forests and gardens. The white tail tips flash in flight and are used in display.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/268175748/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Golden-olive Woodpecker", fact: "A medium-sized woodpecker of Andean forests and foothills with a subtle golden-olive wash across the wings and back. Despite its understated colours it is one of the more commonly encountered woodpeckers across its range, excavating cavities in dead trees used later by other cavity-nesters.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/230630176/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Purple-crowned Fairywren", fact: "The male has a deep violet-purple crown and black mask on an otherwise lavender-blue body — one of Australia's most vividly coloured birds. Like all fairywrens it lives in cooperative groups where helpers assist the dominant pair, and females frequently mate outside the social group.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/394079006/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Chestnut-eared Finch", fact: "A sociable grass finch of Australian grasslands that flocks in large, fast-moving groups. The chestnut ear patch and white rump are distinctive in flight. It is a popular cage bird in Australia and escaped birds have established feral populations elsewhere. It roosts communally in dense vegetation.", photo: "" },
  { name: "Red-capped Robin", fact: "One of Australia's most-loved small birds — jet black with a vivid scarlet cap and breast on the male, suggesting a tiny firefighter's helmet. Found in drier woodland across southern Australia, where it perches prominently on low stumps and drops to the ground to catch insects.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/264963532/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Blue-cheeked Bee-eater", fact: "A large, elegant bee-eater of the Middle East and Central Asia with a turquoise-blue face, green body and long tail streamers. Like all bee-eaters it catches bees and wasps in flight and beats them against a perch to discharge the sting before swallowing. It excavates burrows in flat sandy ground.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/133997490/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "White-browed Coucal", fact: "An African member of the cuckoo family that, unlike most cuckoos, builds its own nest and raises its own young. Its call — a deep, liquid bubbling 'boo-boo-boo' that descends like water gurgling into a bottle — is one of Africa's most characteristic sounds in dense vegetation near water.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/31625/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Yellow-crowned Night Heron", fact: "Hunts crustaceans, especially crabs, with notable dexterity — it manipulates them with its bill to avoid the claws before swallowing. It is the dominant crab predator in many Caribbean and coastal North American marshes. Like all night herons it has blood-red eyes and hunts primarily at dusk.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/208281514/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Buff-spotted Flufftail", fact: "One of Africa's most secretive birds — a tiny, densely spotted rail that creeps through wet forest floor vegetation like a mouse, almost never seen. It is identified primarily by its call: a series of loud explosive hoots that seem completely improbable from a bird its size, often heard in the dead of night.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/66172083/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Grey-headed Albatross", fact: "Makes the fastest circumnavigation of the globe ever recorded for any animal — one bird completed a full circuit in 46 days, powered entirely by wind. It breeds every other year on remote sub-Antarctic islands and can live over 70 years. Its grey head and yellow bill stripe make it one of the more elegant albatrosses.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/74683634/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Brown-hooded Kingfisher", fact: "An African woodland kingfisher that rarely eats fish — it hunts insects, lizards and small frogs on dry land, swooping from a perch onto prey on the ground. The brown hood and red bill distinguish it from its relatives. It uses its heavy bill to excavate nest burrows in earthen banks.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/740247/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "White-backed Night Heron", fact: "A small, secretive African heron with a diagnostic white back visible only in flight. It roosts by day in dense waterside vegetation and is easily overlooked. Unlike other night herons it is generally found singly along heavily wooded rivers and streams rather than in open marshes.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/732765/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Black-chested Snake Eagle", fact: "A specialist snake predator that hovers high on thermals scanning the ground below, then drops onto snakes up to 1.5 metres long. It swallows snakes headfirst — and has been seen with a snake's tail protruding from its bill while the head is already being digested. Immune to many snake venoms.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/213103724/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Rufous-naped Lark", fact: "One of Africa's most musical larks, performing elaborate song flights over open grassland from a conspicuous perch on a termite mound or fence post. It can mimic fragments of other species' songs and weaves them into its own improvised performance. Males have a distinctive rufous patch on the nape.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/735864/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "White-eared Barbet", fact: "An East African barbet with a striking white ear stripe and streaked underparts. Like all barbets it excavates nest holes in dead wood. It eats figs almost exclusively, making it important for seed dispersal in East African forests. Small family groups move together and roost in the same hole.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/136071/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Golden-headed Cisticola", fact: "A tiny African grass warbler whose breeding male develops a bright golden cap. During display he rises high above the grass in fluttering, erratic flight — quite unlike the secretive skulking he does the rest of the year. His nest, woven from spiderwebs and grass, is attached to several grass blades and narrows at the top.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/69100846/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Red-fronted Parrot", fact: "A medium-sized African parrot with a red forehead and green body. Found in forest and woodland from Senegal to Ethiopia, it travels in noisy flocks and is locally common but declining due to trapping for the pet trade. It excavates nest holes in dead wood and roosts communally in tall trees.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/143115351/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Black-faced Antbird", fact: "A small Amazonian antbird that follows army ant swarms to catch the insects, spiders and lizards flushed by the ants — a behaviour called ant-following. It is an 'obligate' ant-follower, meaning it relies heavily on ants for foraging rather than hunting independently. The black face mask is a marker of dominance.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/1461752/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Blue-billed Malimbe", fact: "A West African forest weaver with a striking blue-grey bill and vivid red plumage on the head and breast. Like all malimbes it weaves a beautifully engineered hanging nest from palm fibres, suspended from a branch to deter climbing predators. It travels in small groups within the forest canopy.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/177486135/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Chestnut-capped Blackbird", fact: "A South American icterid with a distinctive chestnut cap on an otherwise glossy black body. Males gather in small choruses to sing from exposed perches in marshy areas, their liquid calls carrying across wetlands. It builds a deep cup nest in low vegetation over or near water.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/70821462/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Yellow-whiskered Greenbul", fact: "A common but cheerful African forest bulbul whose bright yellow 'whisker' stripes light up the dim understorey. It moves through the forest in small groups, announcing itself with frequent chattering calls. It eats small fruits and berries and is an important seed disperser in West African forests.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/50926216/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "White-backed Mousebird", fact: "One of six mousebird species — an African family with no close relatives anywhere else. It has a white lower back that flashes in flight. Mousebirds have uniquely reversible outer toes and hang in clusters to roost, conserving warmth by pressing together. They can enter deep torpor on cold nights.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/138356817/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Grey-backed Fiscal", fact: "A predatory shrike of East African savannah with a grey back, white underparts and a hooked bill. Like all fiscals it impales prey — grasshoppers, lizards, small mice — on thorns, creating a 'larder' to return to later. The grey back distinguishes it from the similar Common Fiscal.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/616655/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Brown-backed Woodpecker", fact: "A small, brown African woodpecker that is easy to overlook but is actually one of the most widely distributed woodpeckers on the continent. It is a generalist that forages on a wide variety of tree species in woodland and savannah, and is less dependent on large old trees than most woodpeckers.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/1939784/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Blue-crowned Hanging Parrot", fact: "Sleeps hanging upside down like a bat from a branch — a unique habit among parrots. The male has a blue crown and a vivid red rump. Found across Southeast Asia from India to Borneo, it feeds primarily on nectar, soft fruit and buds and is an important pollinator of forest trees.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/64901100/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Pale-headed Rosella", fact: "A medium-sized Australian parrot with a creamy white head contrasting with vivid blue-green wings and a blue belly. It frequents open woodland in northeast Australia and is bolder and more conspicuous than most rosellas, often seen foraging on the ground in small groups.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/71282187/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Red-legged Thrush", fact: "The national bird of Dominica, with conspicuous red legs and orbital skin that make it immediately recognisable. It is one of the Caribbean's most widely distributed and adaptable thrushes, found in forest, gardens and scrub across multiple islands. It forages boldly in leaf litter.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/474638905/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Chestnut-flanked White-eye", fact: "A tiny Southeast Asian bird with a neat white eye-ring and warm chestnut flanks. White-eyes form large mixed flocks that move through forest in a constant stream of soft contact calls, gleaning tiny insects and nectar from flowers. They build exquisite cup nests suspended from thin forking branches.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/243491470/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Golden-cheeked Warbler", fact: "The only songbird that breeds exclusively in Texas, nesting only in mature Ashe juniper trees whose shaggy bark it uses for nest material. Critically restricted in range — its entire world breeding population fits in a region roughly the size of Connecticut, and it winters only in a handful of Central American mountain valleys.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/6534514/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Blue-throated Macaw", fact: "Critically endangered, with fewer than 350 individuals remaining in a small area of Bolivian savannah. Long thought extinct until rediscovered in 1992. Unlike most macaws it nests almost exclusively in the cavities of a single palm tree species that is also harvested commercially.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/157595508/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "White-necked Puffbird", fact: "A stocky, large-headed bird of lowland Neotropical forest that sits motionless on a perch for long periods, then sallies out to catch large insects or small lizards. Its head is huge relative to its body, giving it a puffed, 'puffbird' look. Pairs excavate nest burrows in earthen banks.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/60395189/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Purple-rumped Sunbird", fact: "A common sunbird of South and Southeast Asia whose male flashes a metallic purple rump and maroon breast band in brilliant sunlight. It hovers briefly to probe flowers but prefers to perch while feeding. It builds a hanging purse-shaped nest of plant fibres and spiderweb suspended from a thin twig.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/172538925/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "White-bearded Manakin", fact: "Males gather in exploded leks in Neotropical forest where each male clears his own display court on the forest floor, snapping between perches so fast it produces a loud mechanical pop. They 'moonwalk' backward along a branch — genuinely before Michael Jackson — as part of courtship.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/61719716/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Crimson-backed Flameback", fact: "A striking woodpecker of South and Southeast Asian forests with a brilliant crimson back and golden crest. It drums loudly on dead wood and excavates nest cavities that are later used by a wide variety of other cavity-nesting birds and mammals.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/93090252/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Blue-backed Tanager", fact: "A vivid tanager of northwestern South America with an electric blue back and turquoise underparts — colours produced by feather nanostructures rather than pigment. It inhabits humid forest edges and second growth where it feeds on small fruit, often in mixed-species flocks.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/31418134/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Black-and-yellow Broadbill", fact: "A Southeast Asian forest bird with a striking yellow-and-black pattern and an extraordinary circular display flight — the male flies in tight rings around a branch, wing feathers producing a mechanical whirring sound, before landing and puffing up to reveal his vivid blue bill.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/64801633/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Rusty-faced Parrot", fact: "A rare Andean parrot with a warm rusty-orange face contrasting with otherwise green plumage. Found only in fragmented montane forest in Venezuela, Colombia and Ecuador, it travels in small flocks and is rarely encountered. Its unusual colouration and restricted range make it one of South America's more enigmatic parrots.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/73726759/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "White-tailed Nuthatch", fact: "A small nuthatch of Himalayan forests that creeps headfirst down tree trunks in the characteristic nuthatch fashion, probing bark crevices for insects. The white tail base visible in flight distinguishes it from similar species. It often joins mixed-species feeding flocks moving through montane forest.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/263079/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Chestnut-headed Bee-eater", fact: "A strikingly patterned bee-eater of South and Southeast Asia with a rich chestnut head and green body. Like all bee-eaters it removes the sting from bees by beating them against a branch before swallowing. It breeds colonially in burrows dug into flat or gently sloping ground, sometimes in numbers of hundreds.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/116972511/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Yellow-billed Stork", fact: "Uses an unusual feeding technique called 'tactolocation' — wading with its bill slightly open and submerged, closing it the instant a fish touches it. The reaction time (around 25 milliseconds) is one of the fastest reflexes recorded in any vertebrate. Its yellow bill and pink-flushed white plumage are distinctive.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/169210867/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Red-headed Weaver", fact: "One of Africa's most striking weavers, with a vivid scarlet-red head contrasting sharply with a pale bill and blue-grey back. Unlike most weavers it favours woodland and forest edges rather than open grassland. The male builds a distinctive nest with a long entrance tube.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/776680/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Blue-mantled Thornbill", fact: "A tiny Andean hummingbird with a metallic blue-green mantle that flashes brilliantly in mountain sunlight. Like most thornbills it has a short straight bill suited to short tubular flowers, and pierces longer flowers at the base to steal nectar. Found in high Andean scrub and paramo above 3,000 metres.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/146228707/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Grey-capped Warbler", fact: "An African warbler related to wren-warblers, found in dense vegetation near streams and marshes. It creeps through reeds and grass stems mouse-like, rarely emerging into the open, and its presence is usually revealed only by its insistent, sharp contact call.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/258556347/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Buff-banded Rail", fact: "One of the most widely distributed rails in the world — from India to Australia — yet almost never seen because it creeps through dense marsh vegetation. The orange-buff breast band and boldly barred flanks make it one of the more handsomely patterned rails. It has colonised extremely remote Pacific islands on its own.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/38291/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "White-rumped Shama", fact: "Considered one of the finest songsters in Asia — a long, varied, melodious song that can incorporate the calls of many other species. The male is glossy black with a chestnut belly and vivid white rump that flashes in the forest understorey. It was once widely trapped for the cagebird trade.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/279082/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Rufous-backed Robin", fact: "A Mexican and Central American robin found on the opposite side of the country from its usual range during rare winter irruptions into the US Southwest — causing significant excitement among birdwatchers. The rufous back sets it apart from the American Robin, with which it is often confused at a glance.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/253871853/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Golden-winged Warbler", fact: "Hybridises extensively with Blue-winged Warblers wherever their ranges overlap, producing 'Brewster's' and 'Lawrence's' Warblers. In areas of heavy hybridisation the pure Golden-winged disappears within decades. Despite being a conservation concern, basic facts about its winter ecology in Central America are still being pieced together.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/38821205/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Purple-naped Lory", fact: "A vivid red-and-purple lory found only on Seram and nearby islands in the Maluku group of Indonesia. Like all lories it has a brush-tipped tongue adapted for feeding on nectar and pollen rather than seeds. It is threatened by trapping for the pet trade and forest clearance.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/63563327/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Black-capped Donacobius", fact: "A loud and conspicuous South American marsh bird that was once thought to be a wren or mockingbird, but genetic studies revealed it has no close living relatives — it is the sole member of an ancient lineage. Pairs duet constantly while wagging their tails and inflating orange neck pouches.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/191176874/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Orange-backed Woodpecker", fact: "A striking Bornean woodpecker with an orange-gold back and black-and-white streaked head. Restricted to lowland primary forest in Borneo and some Sundaic islands, it is threatened by the near-total loss of its lowland rainforest habitat to oil palm and logging.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/154926548/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "White-crested Hornbill", fact: "A West and Central African forest hornbill with a magnificent cascade of white feathers on its crown. It moves through the forest in noisy family groups, with all members helping to raise the sealed-in female's chicks. Its long tail and flapping flight give it a distinctive, undulating silhouette.", photo: "" },
  { name: "Blue-headed Racket-tail", fact: "A Philippine parrot with a glittering blue head and two elongated tail feathers with naked shafts ending in racket-shaped tips. Found only on Palawan, it feeds on nectar, seeds and small insects in forest and forest edges. Like many Philippine endemics it is threatened by forest loss.", photo: "" },
  { name: "Red-billed Firefinch", fact: "One of Africa's most common and widespread small finches — a tiny crimson bird with a red bill found near human habitation from Senegal to Ethiopia. It is often parasitised by the Violet-backed Indigobird, which mimics its song and lays eggs in its nest, leaving the firefinch to raise the cuckoo's chick.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/468072891/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Yellow-eared Bulbul", fact: "A distinctive Sri Lankan endemic with bright yellow ear patches and a yellow vent. Found in montane forests above 1,000 metres, it is a common bird in the hill country but rarely found elsewhere. It feeds on berries and small insects and is an important seed disperser in Sri Lanka's montane zone.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/92270950/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Grey-necked Wood Rail", fact: "A large, colourful rail of Neotropical wetlands and mangroves with a grey neck, chestnut body and vivid red bill and legs. Despite its bright colours it is surprisingly secretive, creeping through dense vegetation. Its loud, cackling call at dawn and dusk is one of the most characteristic sounds of tropical wetlands.", photo: "" },
  { name: "Tawny-browed Owl", fact: "A medium-sized owl of South American forests distinguished by warm tawny-buff eyebrows. Found in humid forest from Panama to Brazil, it hunts small rodents and large insects from a perch. One of several poorly known South American owls whose distribution and habits are still being mapped by ornithologists.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/452504047/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Chestnut-breasted Wheatear", fact: "A desert wheatear of rocky terrain in the Middle East and Central Asia with a warm chestnut breast and bold black-and-white pattern. It perches prominently on boulders and makes short runs across the ground to catch insects. Like all wheatears, it migrates to Africa for the winter.", photo: "" },
  { name: "White-lored Oriole", fact: "A Philippine endemic oriole found only on Luzon and nearby islands, with bright yellow plumage and a distinctive white loral patch between the bill and eye. It inhabits forest canopy where it feeds on insects and fruit, and is one of several Philippine orioles found nowhere else in the world.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/6246960/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Brown-winged Starling", fact: "A starling of the Lesser Sunda Islands of Indonesia with glossy black plumage and distinctly brown wings that flash in flight. It is found in open woodland, scrub and gardens near human habitation, where it feeds on fruit and insects, and has a loud, varied call.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/269651620/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Rufous-sided Crake", fact: "A tiny, secretive South American rail that creeps through dense marsh vegetation at the water's edge, almost never emerging into the open. Its rufous flanks are boldly barred with black and white. Like most crakes it is far more often heard — a rapid trilling call — than seen.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/922856/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Golden-tailed Parrotlet", fact: "A tiny Amazonian parrot with golden tail patches that flash brilliantly in flight. Parrotlets are the smallest parrots in the Americas, and despite their diminutive size they are known for feisty, assertive personalities. This species travels in small, fast-moving flocks through lowland forest and forest edges.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/187592531/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Grey-hooded Attila", fact: "A large, noisy flycatcher of South American forest whose loud, ringing whistle rings through the canopy but the bird itself is surprisingly difficult to spot. Like other attilas it sits upright in the mid-canopy and sallies out to catch large insects. Its grey hood distinguishes it from similar species.", photo: "" },
  { name: "Dusky-billed Parrotlet", fact: "A tiny, fast-moving parrot of lowland South American forest that travels in small flocks and feeds on seeds and fruit in the forest understorey. Its dusky bill distinguishes it from several similar parrotlets. Like all parrotlets it is highly vocal, with a rapid chattering call heard constantly as the flock moves.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/70512681/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Black-banded Crake", fact: "A poorly known South American rail with distinctive black-and-white barring on the flanks and a black breast band. It inhabits marshes and wet grasslands in Amazonia and is so rarely seen that aspects of its ecology remain almost entirely unknown. It is identified mainly by a sharp, repeated call from dense cover.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/361277879/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Tawny-chested Flycatcher", fact: "A small flycatcher of Central American highland forest with warm tawny underparts and an upright posture. It forages alone or in pairs in the mid-storey, often joining mixed-species flocks. Found only in Costa Rica and Panama's cloud forests, it is one of many poorly-documented highland flycatchers.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/360057844/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Cinnamon-rumped Foliage-gleaner", fact: "A brownish Amazonian bird that creeps through the lower forest levels like a nuthatch, systematically searching dead leaf clusters and vine tangles for hidden insects and spiders. Its cinnamon rump is the key field mark. Foliage-gleaners are a large, notoriously difficult-to-identify group of Neotropical birds.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/252604038/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "White-shouldered Fire-eye", fact: "A small Amazonian antbird with a brilliant white shoulder patch and a vivid red iris. Males are jet black with the white patch; females are rufous-brown. Like many antbirds it follows army ant swarms to feed on fleeing invertebrates. The fiery eye is used in territorial displays between males.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/139367700/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Dusky-throated Antshrike", fact: "A secretive Amazonian antbird that creeps through dense undergrowth in the lower forest levels. The male is dark grey with a finely barred throat; the female is rufous-brown. Despite being common in suitable Amazonian habitat, basic aspects of its breeding biology were described only in recent decades.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/334607253/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Brown-chested Jungle Flycatcher", fact: "A dull brown flycatcher of Southeast Asian forests that perches in the mid-storey and sallies out to catch insects. It belongs to a group of Asian jungle flycatchers that are notoriously difficult to identify in the field, often requiring careful observation of subtle plumage details or listening for the distinctive call.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/319287135/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Rufous-throated Bronze Cuckoo", fact: "A small parasitic cuckoo of Australia and New Guinea that lays its eggs in the nests of gerygones — tiny warblers. The gerygone chick, once hatched alongside the cuckoo chick, is heaved out of the nest. The cuckoo chick then mimics the calls of multiple gerygone chicks at once to demand enough food from the exhausted foster parents.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/65166780/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Tawny-winged Woodcreeper", fact: "A Neotropical woodcreeper that spirals up tree trunks gleaning insects from bark, like a treecreeper. The warm tawny-buff wings are distinctive in flight. It often follows army ant swarms and joins the chaotic multi-species assemblages that form above the advancing ant columns.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/35066440/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "White-browed Tit-warbler", fact: "A tiny, jewel-like bird of Himalayan and Chinese mountain scrub — the male is a vivid mosaic of lavender, blue and chestnut with a white eyebrow. Despite its striking colours it is hard to see in dense scrub. It descends to lower elevations in winter with other montane species in mixed feeding flocks.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/404620244/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Rufous-capped Nunlet", fact: "A small, round-headed Amazonian puffbird with a warm rufous cap. Like other nunlets it sits patiently on low perches in the forest understorey, watching for large insects before sallying out to catch them. It lives in humid forest and forest edges and is more often heard than seen.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/117687756/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Black-tipped Cotinga", fact: "A cotinga of the high Andes in which the male is iridescent blue with a distinctive black tip to each wing feather visible when perched. Found from Venezuela to Bolivia in humid montane forest, it feeds on fruit in the upper canopy and is rarely seen at lower levels.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/55649951/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Yellow-green Vireo", fact: "A common migratory vireo of Central America and southern North America with a distinctive yellow wash to its underparts and sides. Like all vireos it is a methodical insect gleaner, moving slowly through the canopy and peering carefully at leaves before picking off caterpillars and beetles.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/626438/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Chestnut-crowned Antpitta", fact: "A large, round, near-tailless ground bird of Andean forest with a vivid chestnut cap. Antpittas bounce on long legs through the forest understorey, but are far more often heard than seen. Like several other antpittas, individuals have been tamed with earthworms and will walk up to regular feeding stations.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/185130806/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "White-ringed Flycatcher", fact: "A boldly marked Neotropical flycatcher with a striking white eye-ring that makes it look permanently startled. Found from Costa Rica to Bolivia in forest edges and second growth, it perches upright and sallies out to catch insects. The contrast between its dark upper parts and white underparts is eye-catching.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/358303479/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Buff-rumped Warbler", fact: "A Neotropical warbler that forages by walking along forest stream edges, bobbing its bright buff rump constantly like a wagtail — an unusual behaviour for a warbler. It nests inside ball-shaped structures of dead leaves placed on exposed stream banks, perfectly camouflaged against flood debris.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/422696080/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Red-masked Parakeet", fact: "A bright green parakeet of Ecuador and Peru with an entirely red head, sometimes confused with the Cherry-headed Conure. Feral populations in San Francisco and San Diego have formed large flocks and are featured in the documentary 'The Wild Parrots of Telegraph Hill', where escaped pets became a beloved urban spectacle.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/215867200/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Blue-and-yellow Tanager", fact: "A widespread Andean tanager with vivid blue upperparts and warm yellow underparts. It inhabits open woodland, gardens and shrubby forest edges from Venezuela to Argentina, and is one of the more commonly seen colourful birds in Andean towns and parks. It feeds on fruit, berries and insects.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/169931554/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Grey-mantled Wren", fact: "A poorly known wren of cloud forest in Ecuador and Peru with an unusual grey back unlike the brown tones of most wrens. Like all wrens in the Neotropics it skulks in dense undergrowth and is almost always heard before being seen — the loud, bubbling song giving away its presence before the bird itself appears.", photo: "" },
  { name: "Orange-crowned Euphonia", fact: "A tiny but vivid tanager of South America with a glowing orange crown patch on an otherwise blue-black male. Euphonias are specialist mistletoe-berry eaters and are important dispersers of mistletoe seeds, depositing them on host trees as they pass through. The female is yellow-green and far less conspicuous.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/47444537/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Black-eared Cuckoo", fact: "A small, secretive Australian cuckoo with a distinctive black ear patch. It parasitises the nests of several small songbirds, particularly thornbills and gerygones, and is often heard calling — a descending, slightly mournful whistle — without being seen. Found across much of inland Australia in dry scrub.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/103161/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Rufous-bellied Seedsnipe", fact: "Not a snipe at all but a peculiar South American shorebird with the plumage of a partridge and the lifestyle of a high-altitude grazer. It feeds on plant seeds and tubers in Andean puna grassland above 4,000 metres, crouching to the ground when disturbed so that its mottled plumage blends with the grass tussocks.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/260760138/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "White-chinned Petrel", fact: "One of the most numerous seabirds in the Southern Ocean, with a population in the tens of millions. The small white patch on its chin varies from barely visible to quite prominent, confusing early taxonomists who thought they had found separate species. It follows fishing vessels and is killed in large numbers on longlines.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/93091647/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Chestnut-collared Longspur", fact: "A North American grassland sparrow with a striking chestnut collar and black belly on breeding males, named for the elongated hind claw that helps it grip grass stems. It breeds on shortgrass prairies and has declined sharply as native prairie is converted to agriculture — one of North America's fastest-declining birds.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/55766380/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Yellow-crowned Amazon", fact: "A stocky, gregarious parrot of Caribbean islands and Central American coasts with a yellow crown patch and vivid green body. It is capable of mimicking human speech and has been kept as a pet for centuries. Wild flocks are noisy and conspicuous, roosting communally and travelling in raucous groups.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/473737022/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Brown-capped Vireo", fact: "A small vireo of Andean cloud forest and woodland edges from Mexico to Bolivia, with a distinctive brown cap. Like all vireos it is a methodical insect hunter in the forest canopy and mid-storey, often joining mixed-species flocks. Its song is a repetitive series of short phrases.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/570921/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Tawny-crowned Pygmy Tyrant", fact: "One of the smallest flycatchers in South America — barely 8 cm long — with an eye-catching tawny crown patch erected during displays. It inhabits grass and scrub at forest edges where it sallies from a low perch to catch tiny insects. Despite its size it is aggressive toward rival males near its territory.", photo: "" },
  { name: "Pale-vented Pigeon", fact: "A large, pale pigeon of lowland Neotropical forest and forest edges with a pale vent and reddish-brown upperparts. It travels in small groups between fruiting trees and nests in loose colonies. Despite being hunted for food across its range, it remains common in many areas of Amazonia.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/311472350/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Red-throated Pipit", fact: "Breeds on Arctic tundra in Scandinavia and Siberia and winters in Africa and Asia. In breeding plumage the face and throat are a warm apricot-red, strikingly different from its pale winter dress. It is one of the most sought-after rare migrants when it turns up on the British coastline each autumn.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/96825051/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Grey-and-buff Woodpecker", fact: "A medium-sized woodpecker of Southeast Asian forest with a delicate pattern of grey, buff and black. Found from the Himalayan foothills to Borneo, it forages on large tree trunks and branches, and like most Asian woodpeckers is less conspicuous and more skulking than the boldly patterned species of other continents.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/4793879/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "White-naped Tit", fact: "A small Indian tit found only in dry deciduous forest and scrub in parts of peninsular India — one of the most range-restricted tits in the world. The white nape is its clearest distinguishing feature. It is rarely encountered and little studied, with basic ecology only partly described.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/240800/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Rufous-winged Sparrow", fact: "A sparrow of rocky desert grassland in southern Arizona and Mexico, with rufous wing bars and a distinctive head striping. It is one of the few sparrows that sings a complex song year-round rather than just in breeding season. It is extremely sedentary and rarely travels far from its natal territory.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/341702482/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Black-browed Albatross", fact: "The most numerous and widely distributed albatross in the Southern Ocean, with a bold black eyebrow stripe and yellow bill. It follows fishing vessels for discarded bycatch and is killed in enormous numbers on longlines, making it one of the albatrosses most at risk from fisheries bycatch mortality.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/171871704/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Golden-breasted Starling", fact: "Considered the most beautiful starling in the world — an extraordinary metallic mosaic of green, violet, blue and golden yellow, with a long graduated tail. Found in dry acacia woodland in East Africa, it travels in small groups and nests in tree holes, often near human settlements.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/349187099/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Chestnut-mandibled Toucan", fact: "A large, noisy toucan of Central and South American forest with a massive two-toned bill — chestnut on the lower mandible, yellow on the upper. It travels in small raucous groups through the canopy in search of fruit, and its yelping calls carry far through the forest. It swallows whole the fruit that other birds peck at.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/83630887/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Blue-rumped Parrot", fact: "A small parrot of Southeast Asian forest distinctive for its vivid blue rump that flashes brilliantly as it flies. It feeds on seeds, buds and small fruit in the forest canopy and is most often seen flying fast and low between forest patches. Threatened by trapping for the pet trade.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/253722041/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "White-bellied Woodstar", fact: "A tiny hummingbird of Andean foothills — the male has an iridescent purple-pink gorget and a gleaming white belly. Like most woodstars it is fast and aggressive, defending flower patches from larger hummingbirds. It can enter daily torpor on cold Andean nights, dropping its heart rate to just a few beats per minute.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/567467/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Tawny-tufted Toucanet", fact: "A smaller relative of the large toucans with a tawny-orange tuft of feathers around the bill base. Found in Amazonian forest, it travels in small groups through the canopy feeding on fruit. Smaller bill size means it can access smaller fruit clusters than its larger relatives, reducing competition.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/157179038/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Red-and-green Macaw", fact: "The largest macaw in the world by length, with a wingspan up to 125 cm. The vivid red, blue and green plumage is offset by fine red feather lines on the bare white face patch — actually individual tiny feathers growing from the skin. Pairs mate for life and can live over 60 years.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/103212299/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Buff-necked Ibis", fact: "A large, noisy ibis of South American grasslands with a distinctive pale buff-coloured neck. It walks through open pastures and wetlands probing for invertebrates, and often forages alongside cattle. Its loud, harsh calls carry great distances, giving away its presence long before it is seen.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/9867600/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Yellow-billed Cotinga", fact: "A rare cotinga of the Pacific slope forests of Costa Rica and Panama. The male is a pure brilliant white with a yellow bill; the female is brown-streaked. It is considered one of Costa Rica's most sought-after birds, found only in a narrow strip of lowland forest that has been heavily reduced by deforestation.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/167493116/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Grey-rumped Swiftlet", fact: "One of the edible nest swiftlets whose cup-shaped nests — built entirely from the bird's own hardened saliva — are harvested for bird's nest soup. A single nest takes the bird up to 35 days to build, and top-quality white nests can sell for over $3,000 per kilogram in Asian markets.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/362802199/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "White-shouldered Ibis", fact: "A critically endangered ibis of Borneo and nearby islands with distinctive white patches on the shoulders. It is one of Southeast Asia's most threatened waterbirds, with the total population probably under 250 individuals, declining due to wetland drainage and persecution. Almost nothing is known about its breeding biology.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/178251484/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Rufous-fronted Thornbird", fact: "An Amazonian ovenbird that builds elaborate stick nests — huge communal structures that can contain multiple chambers used by different pairs. Nests are used year after year and may eventually become so large and heavy that they cause the supporting branch to break. The rufous forehead is the key identification feature.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/564941769/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Chestnut-winged Cuckoo", fact: "A large, striking cuckoo of South and Southeast Asian forest with vivid chestnut wings and a long graduated tail. It is one of the few parasitic cuckoos that sometimes raises its own young in addition to parasitising other species. Its loud, nasal call rings through the forest at dawn.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/1083575/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Blue-crowned Trogon", fact: "A widespread Neotropical trogon with a metallic blue crown and brilliant red belly. Like all trogons it has an unusual foot structure — two toes forward and two back, but with different toe arrangements — and sits upright, motionless for long periods before sallying out to pick fruit or insects.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/1752802/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Black-spotted Barbet", fact: "An Amazonian barbet with bold black spotting on white underparts and a red and yellow head. Like other Neotropical barbets it excavates nest holes in rotting wood. Pairs are strongly bonded and engage in loud antiphonal duetting in which both birds contribute to a song that sounds like a single performer.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/61746083/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "White-whiskered Puffbird", fact: "A stocky, large-headed puffbird with a striking white moustache and a habit of sitting completely motionless on a low perch for extended periods. It hunts beetles and lizards by sight and sallies out to catch them on the ground. It nests in an earthen tunnel dug into a sloping bank.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/3276355/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Yellow-tufted Woodpecker", fact: "A large Amazonian woodpecker with vivid yellow tufts on the sides of its head. It is one of several closely related black-and-yellow woodpeckers in South America that are notoriously difficult to tell apart in the field. It hammers dead trees and strips bark to find large beetle grubs.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/361342870/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Grey-chinned Minivet", fact: "A small, colourful bird of Asian montane forest. The male is red and black; the female is yellow and grey. Minivets travel in restless, fast-moving flocks through the forest canopy and are among the most conspicuous birds in Asian hill forests, their flickering colours visible as the flock passes overhead.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/6524387/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Rufous-tailed Scrub Robin", fact: "A secretive chat of arid scrub and open woodland across the Middle East and Central Asia with a warm rufous tail it cocks and fans while foraging. It hops low through dense undergrowth and is more often heard than seen. Its song is a loud, varied and melodious series of phrases.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/66245232/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Brown-flanked Bush Warbler", fact: "A small, skulking warbler of dense undergrowth in Himalayan and Chinese forests. It creeps mouse-like through dense bamboo and grass, rarely rising more than a metre above the ground. Like other bush warblers it is identified primarily by its song — a loud, explosive 'pick-piooo' — rather than its drab brown plumage.", photo: "" },
  { name: "Pale-crowned Cisticola", fact: "An African grassland warbler with a pale crown that becomes even paler in breeding plumage. It performs display flights above the grass, rising and falling while calling, then drops back into the grass and disappears. It is one of many nearly identical cisticola species that drive African bird identification to its limits.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/2444879/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Black-throated Wattle-eye", fact: "A small, vivid flycatcher of Central African forest with a bright red eye-wattle and a black throat bordered below by a white breast. Wattle-eyes snap their bills audibly while foraging — giving an audible click that betrays their presence in the forest understorey even when the bird is hidden.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/6038170/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Red-winged Pytilia", fact: "A small African finch with a red bill and wing patches that flashes brilliantly as it feeds on seeds in dry savannah. It is the primary host of the Paradise Whydah, which lays its eggs in pytilia nests. The pytilia chick's mouth markings are precisely mimicked by the whydah chick to deceive its foster parents.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/1098652/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "White-spotted Flufftail", fact: "A tiny African rail — barely the size of a sparrow — that is almost never seen despite being heard regularly. It gives a deep, booming series of calls from dense grass that seem far too loud for such a small bird. Pairs call in duet and researchers have struggled to record basic facts about its life cycle.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/6045014/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Chestnut-backed Buttonquail", fact: "A tiny, ground-dwelling Australian bird with sex roles reversed — the female, more boldly marked, holds a territory and calls to attract males. After laying, she leaves the male to incubate and raise the chicks alone, while she may mate with additional males. It runs rather than flies when disturbed.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/175564394/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Golden-spectacled Warbler", fact: "A lively warbler of Himalayan and Southeast Asian mountain forest with vivid yellow 'spectacle' markings around its eyes. It moves constantly through the undergrowth and lower canopy, often cocking its short tail. Despite its striking head pattern it is often overlooked in its dense montane habitat.", photo: "" },
  { name: "Black-capped Social Weaver", fact: "Builds communal nests up to 1.5 metres wide in acacia trees shared by multiple pairs — each with its own chamber. Groups of up to 500 birds have been reported sharing a single massive nest. Unlike the more famous Sociable Weaver, it is confined to dry thorn scrub in Kenya and Tanzania.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/306479462/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Yellow-mantled Widowbird", fact: "A striking African widowbird with a bright yellow shoulder patch on an otherwise black body. During the breeding season the male performs undulating display flights over grassland to attract females, the yellow mantle flashing conspicuously. Outside breeding season males moult to plain brown and become hard to identify.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/225154/medium.JPG" },
  { name: "Olive-headed Weaver", fact: "A poorly known East African weaver with an olive-green head and yellow-streaked underparts. It inhabits the canopy of miombo woodland in Tanzania and Mozambique — a habitat that is poorly studied compared to more accessible African ecosystems. It weaves a typical weaver nest suspended from the branch tips.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/66691480/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Purple-banded Sunbird", fact: "A small East African sunbird with a diagnostic band of metallic purple across an otherwise metallic green breast. The female is dull olive-yellow, completely unlike the male. It feeds at a wide variety of flowers, probing with its curved bill, and is common in forest edges and gardens throughout coastal East Africa.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/31406789/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "White-fronted Scops Owl", fact: "A tiny owl of Sub-Saharan African woodlands with a distinctive white forehead. Like other scops owls it relies on cryptic streaked plumage to roost invisibly against tree bark, stretching upright with eyes slitted when alarmed. Its call is a soft, monotonous whistle repeated through the night.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/58477731/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Buff-crested Bustard", fact: "A small East African bustard with a prominent pale buff crest that is erected during courtship displays. Males perform exaggerated bowing and crest-raising in open scrub, accompanied by a strange clucking call. Unlike larger bustards, it inhabits dense thornbush rather than open plains.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/190388074/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Brown-headed Paradise Kingfisher", fact: "A strikingly beautiful New Guinea kingfisher with vivid blue and red plumage and elongated central tail feathers. Despite its brilliant colours, it inhabits the dark forest understorey and is often first detected by its loud, descending call. It hunts lizards and large insects rather than fish.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/8910547/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Rufous-bellied Kookaburra", fact: "A forest kookaburra of New Guinea with a warm rufous belly quite unlike the white-bellied Laughing Kookaburra. It gives a loud, machine-gun-like laugh like its relative but is less widely known. It hunts large insects, lizards and small snakes by dropping from a perch onto prey on the ground.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/380885232/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Chestnut-breasted Cuckoo", fact: "A parasitic cuckoo of Australia and New Guinea that lays its eggs exclusively in the nests of thornbills. The cuckoo chick, once it hatches, expels the thornbill's own eggs with special muscular contractions of its back. Found only in rainforest, it is rarely seen despite its distinctive call.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/4245092/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Black-sided Flowerpecker", fact: "A tiny flowerpecker of lowland forest in New Guinea with a bold black stripe down its white side. Flowerpeckers are important dispersers of mistletoe seeds, eating the sticky berries and wiping their bills on branches to dislodge the seeds, inadvertently planting them on future host trees.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/445581879/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "White-bellied Erpornis", fact: "A small, active bird of South and Southeast Asian forest once considered a yuhina, then a vireo-like bird, before being placed in its own family. It has a neat crest and white underparts and moves restlessly through the forest canopy in mixed-species flocks, gleaning tiny insects from leaves.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/4168707/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Golden-fronted Leafbird", fact: "A brilliantly coloured Asian leafbird with a golden forehead and vivid green, blue and black plumage. Males are excellent mimics and incorporate the calls of many other species into their own loud songs. They are aggressive defenders of nectar sources and will chase birds much larger than themselves.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/510309/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Tawny-breasted Honeyeater", fact: "An Australian and New Guinea honeyeater with a warm tawny breast and a long curved bill for probing flowers. Honeyeaters are the ecological equivalent of hummingbirds in Australasia, pollinating a huge variety of flowering plants. This species is particularly fond of melaleuca blossoms.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/350188415/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Blue-faced Parrotfinch", fact: "A small seed-eating finch of Australia and the Pacific with a vivid blue mask that seems to have been painted on. Flocks travel fast and low between grass seed sources. It has established feral populations in Hawaii from escaped cage birds. The blue face intensifies with age and dominance.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/60082504/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Scarlet-backed Flowerpecker", fact: "The male has a brilliant scarlet back that seems almost to glow against the dark canopy of Asian forests. It is one of the most widespread flowerpeckers in Southeast Asia, found in forest, gardens and parks. Its small size and fast movements make it hard to observe despite the male's conspicuous colouring.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/1145037/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Grey-headed Canary-Flycatcher", fact: "A small flycatcher of South and Southeast Asian forest with a grey head, yellow underparts and a habit of flicking its tail nervously. Despite the 'canary' in its name it is a flycatcher, sallying from a perch to catch insects. It is a regular member of mixed-species flocks in montane forest.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/28594635/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Red-capped Flowerpecker", fact: "A tiny flowerpecker of Australasia with a vivid red cap on an otherwise grey and white bird. Like all flowerpeckers it feeds largely on mistletoe berries and is an important disperser of these parasitic plants. The red cap is much more vivid in males than in females.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/84189973/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Brown-throated Sunbird", fact: "One of the most common and widespread sunbirds in Southeast Asia, found in forest, gardens and mangroves from the Malay Peninsula to the Philippines. The male's brown throat is the identification key among the complex of similar green-and-brown sunbirds. It is an important pollinator of garden and forest flowers.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/107800431/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Black-headed Bulbul", fact: "A Southeast Asian bulbul with a glossy black head and olive-green body that inhabits forest edges and secondary growth. Bulbuls are among the most important fruit-eating birds in Asian forests, dispersing seeds over long distances. This species is particularly common in disturbed habitats and along forest margins.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/61128982/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Crimson-winged Woodpecker", fact: "A large Bornean woodpecker with vivid crimson wing patches and a red crest. It is found only in primary lowland and hill forest in Borneo and is rarely seen above the canopy. The destruction of Borneo's lowland forest has severely reduced the areas of suitable habitat available to it.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/189927665/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "White-bellied Minivet", fact: "A minivet of the Sundaic lowlands — Sumatra, Borneo and nearby islands — found in forest canopy where mixed-species flocks move rapidly overhead. The male has a white belly contrasting with his black-and-red pattern. Minivets are among the first birds to abandon degraded forest, making them indicators of forest quality.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/51788071/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Orange-bellied Flowerpecker", fact: "A flowerpecker of South and Southeast Asia with a vivid orange belly patch. It inhabits forest canopy and forest edges, feeding on mistletoe berries and small fruit. The colour signals its dominance at food sources — the brighter the belly, the more successfully it defends patches from rival flowerpeckers.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/11030102/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Black-and-crimson Oriole", fact: "A striking Bornean endemic with jet-black plumage and vivid crimson underparts. Found only in montane forest on Borneo above 900 metres, it is one of the island's most spectacular birds. It feeds on fruit and insects in the canopy, often accompanying mixed-species flocks.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/219938609/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Rufous-winged Philentoma", fact: "A beautiful flycatcher-like bird of Sundaic lowland forest with a slate-blue body and warm rufous wings. Despite its colour it is easily overlooked in the forest understorey, where it forages quietly for insects and small fruit. It belongs to a small family found only in the Malay region.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/206545228/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Blue-winged Leafbird", fact: "One of the most vivid birds of Southeast Asian forests — the male has brilliant blue wings, a golden head and a black throat. It is an important pollinator of canopy trees and a notorious mimic of other species' songs. Pairs maintain contact with a complex, varied duet.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/59229984/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Cream-vented Bulbul", fact: "A common bulbul of Southeast Asian lowland forest, but one that is interesting to ornithologists for its variation: populations across its range differ in eye colour — some have white irises, others red — apparently without hybridising at contact zones, suggesting subtle ecological or behavioural differences.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/11083589/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Grey-hooded Broadbill", fact: "A small broadbill of Southeast Asian forest with a grey hood and vivid yellow underparts. Broadbills have unusually wide, flattened bills for catching large insects in flight. This species inhabits the understorey of primary forest and is rarely seen above the lower canopy. The nest is a hanging pouch of plant fibres.", photo: "" },
  { name: "Dusky Broadbill", fact: "A large, dark broadbill of South and Southeast Asian forest that travels in noisy groups. Unlike most broadbills it has a massive, wide pinkish bill used to snatch large insects and lizards. Groups of up to 10 birds cooperate to mob predators, producing a cacophony of harsh, nasal calls.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/236258430/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Green Broadbill", fact: "A vivid emerald-green broadbill of Southeast Asian rainforest that blends so well with the leafy canopy that it is almost invisible despite its vivid colour. The bright green is created by feather nanostructure rather than pigment. It feeds on figs, hovering briefly to pluck them from branches.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/207942391/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Silver-breasted Broadbill", fact: "A beautiful broadbill of South and Southeast Asian forest with a silvery white breast and colourful head. It builds a large, dangling pear-shaped nest suspended from a branch overhanging a stream — the entrance hole at the side is covered by a porch-like flap of woven plant material.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/8562783/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Red-throated Barbet", fact: "A Sundaic lowland barbet with a vivid red throat and complex patterns of yellow, black and green on the face. It excavates nest holes in dead wood with repeated chisel-like blows of its stout bill. Pairs duet continuously in the forest canopy, producing a synchronised mechanical 'took-took-took.'", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/88518724/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Yellow-crowned Barbet", fact: "A large, vivid barbet of Bornean lowland forest with a yellow crown and blue face. It is an important disperser of fruit seeds in the rainforest. Like all Asian barbets it calls with a loud, repetitive metronomic note that is one of the defining background sounds of the tropical forest.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/153103987/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Golden-whiskered Barbet", fact: "One of the most stunning barbets in Southeast Asia — vivid green with yellow and red facial markings and a golden 'whisker' stripe. Found from the Malay Peninsula to Borneo, it inhabits the canopy of primary and tall secondary forest where it feeds on figs and other soft fruit.", photo: "" },
  { name: "Black-browed Barbet", fact: "A Sundaic barbet with a distinctive black eyebrow stripe and a complex mosaic of colours on its head. It is found only in lowland forest on the Malay Peninsula and Borneo, and is threatened by the widespread conversion of lowland forest to oil palm and timber plantations.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/84503910/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "White-chested Babbler", fact: "A small babbler of coastal mangroves and scrub in the Malay Peninsula, Sumatra and Borneo with a bright white breast. It creeps through dense tangled vegetation near water, and pairs sing persistent, musical duets. It is often the first bird encountered in coastal mangrove habitat.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/20498458/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Rufous-tailed Tailorbird", fact: "A tiny warbler of Southeast Asian scrub that literally sews leaves together with plant fibres and spiderweb to create a cup-shaped nest pouch — one of the most remarkable nest-building techniques in the animal kingdom. It lives up to its name: the needle-and-thread technique pulls leaf edges into a wrap.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/251553023/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Fluffy-backed Tit-babbler", fact: "A small babbler of Southeast Asian lowland forest with a distinctive fluffy white patch on its lower back visible when perched. It moves through the forest understorey in restless, noisy pairs, frequently twitching its wings and tail. Its song is a loud, repeated series of clear whistles.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/25268705/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Chestnut-rumped Babbler", fact: "A small Sundaic forest babbler found low in the understorey and on the ground in primary lowland forest. The warm chestnut rump is visible in flight. It forages by searching through dead leaves and bark for small insects and spiders, often in pairs or small family groups.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/209061634/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Black-throated Babbler", fact: "A compact, short-tailed babbler of Sundaic lowland forest with a black bib and warm brown plumage. It inhabits the densest understorey vegetation, rarely venturing above 2 metres. Pairs duet with a mellow, ringing whistle that is one of the most musical sounds in Bornean forest.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/178792244/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Ferruginous Babbler", fact: "A rich rufous-red babbler of Sundaic lowland forest whose deep ferruginous colour makes it look as if it has been soaked in rust. It forages in pairs in dense vegetation near the forest floor. Found only in the Sundaic lowlands, it is threatened by loss of its primary forest habitat.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/23473686/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Striped Wren-Babbler", fact: "A tiny, striped babbler of Southeast Asian forest floor that creeps through fallen leaves like a mouse, almost never seen in the open. It is identified mainly by its song — a loud, clear whistle repeated persistently at ground level. Despite its common name it is neither a wren nor a babbler in the strict sense.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/45817286/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Marbled Wren-Babbler", fact: "A strikingly patterned wren-babbler with a marbled black-and-white pattern on its head and neck. Found in primary hill and montane forest in the Malay region, it forages on or near the ground in dense understorey. Like other wren-babblers it has tiny vestigial wings and barely flies.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/60327626/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Short-tailed Babbler", fact: "Has the proportionally shortest tail of any babbler — barely visible as a stub — giving it a rounded, neckless appearance. It creeps through the lowest levels of Sundaic forest understorey, close to the ground. Its loud, complex song is entirely out of scale with its dumpy little body.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/212741086/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Brown Fulvetta", fact: "A small, sociable babbler of South and Southeast Asian forest that moves through the understorey in restless groups. Fulvettas are the 'tit-babblers' of Asian forests — energetic, often noisy, and important members of mixed-species flocks that sweep through the forest in waves.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/11130289/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Mountain Fulvetta", fact: "A small, streaked fulvetta of Himalayan and Chinese montane forest that inhabits dense bamboo and rhododendron undergrowth. It moves in small groups through the shrub layer, gleaning insects from leaves and buds. Its soft, repetitive call is a constant presence in Himalayan hillside forests.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/266086018/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Grey-cheeked Fulvetta", fact: "A tiny fulvetta of South and Southeast Asian montane forest with a grey cheek patch and a streaked brown back. It is a regular member of mixed-species flocks in mountain forest, gleaning insects from small branches and leaves with rapid, methodical movements.", photo: "" },
  { name: "Golden-breasted Fulvetta", fact: "A small, vivid fulvetta of Himalayan and Chinese forests with a warm golden-yellow breast. It forages in small flocks through the lower forest canopy, and in autumn joins the great waves of mixed-species flocks that pour through mountain valleys. Its song is a pleasant, high-pitched series of notes.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/173963443/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Black-browed Reed Warbler", fact: "A small Asian reed warbler with a broad black eyebrow stripe, breeding in reeds and tall grass from the Himalayas to Japan. Like all reed warblers it is an excellent mimic. It spends the winter deep in the reedbeds of South and Southeast Asia, where it skulks and rarely shows itself.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/2742851/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Thick-billed Warbler", fact: "One of the larger Old World warblers, with a notably heavy bill used to tackle larger prey than most warblers attempt. It is an extraordinary singer — able to sustain complex song for long periods — and mimics many other species fluently. It breeds in Siberia and winters in South and Southeast Asia.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/103338390/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Striated Grassbird", fact: "A large, streaked warbler of tall grasslands and reedbeds from India to the Philippines. It perches on grass stems and reed tops and delivers a loud, cheerful, varied song. Unlike most warblers it is easy to observe — it often sings from exposed perches rather than hiding in vegetation.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/252853360/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Rufous-rumped Grassbird", fact: "A grassland warbler of the Indian subcontinent and Southeast Asia with a warm rufous rump visible in flight. It inhabits tall grass and scrub near water, and is far more often heard than seen. The male sings from the top of a grass stem before plunging back into the grass like a stone.", photo: "" },
  { name: "Marsh Babbler", fact: "A small, rarely photographed babbler of wet grassland and scrub in Bangladesh, northeast India and Myanmar. It lives in extremely dense grass and reed thickets and is almost impossible to see. Known mainly from its calls — a harsh scolding chatter — and classified as near-threatened due to habitat loss.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/8854379/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "White-crested Laughingthrush", fact: "A gregarious forest babbler of the Himalayas and Southeast Asia with a vivid white crest and a habit of living in noisy groups of 6–20 birds. Laughingthrushes are among the most sociable birds in Asian forests, roosting together and mobbing predators collectively with spectacular noise.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/20167144/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Chestnut-crowned Laughingthrush", fact: "A large Himalayan laughingthrush with a deep chestnut crown and a slate-grey body. Groups move together through the forest understory in a constant stream of soft calls, pausing to search dead leaf clusters. They are bold and curious, often approaching observers who make 'pishing' sounds.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/9900523/medium.jpeg" },
  { name: "Black-faced Laughingthrush", fact: "A laughingthrush of Chinese mountain forest with a striking black facial mask and a white eye-ring. Like most laughingthrushes it is intensely social, moving in groups and roosting communally. Pairs reinforce their bond with antiphonal duets — each bird contributing alternating phrases seamlessly.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/528498690/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Scaly Laughingthrush", fact: "Has scale-like patterning created by dark feather edges that give it a fish-scale appearance across the breast and flanks. Found in Himalayan and southern Chinese forest, it forms large wintering flocks that can number in the hundreds, stripping fruiting trees of berries with remarkable efficiency.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/40623612/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Streaked Laughingthrush", fact: "A heavily streaked laughingthrush of Himalayan oak and rhododendron forest that is a classic member of the mixed-species flocks that sweep through the hillside forests each autumn and winter. It is among the most numerous and widespread laughingthrushes across the Himalayas.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/555209/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Blue-winged Laughingthrush", fact: "A spectacular laughingthrush with vivid blue wings, a grey body and chestnut underparts. Found in the forests of southwest China and adjacent countries, it is considered one of the most beautiful laughingthrushes. Groups move through the mid-canopy, filling the forest with a rich variety of calls.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/40675448/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "White-gorgeted Flycatcher", fact: "A small, retiring flycatcher of Himalayan and Southeast Asian montane forest with a neat white throat gorget. It perches low in the forest understorey and makes short sallies to catch insects in the air or from leaves. Found at mid-elevations in dense, humid forest from Nepal to southwest China.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/18298693/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Rufous-chested Flycatcher", fact: "A small flycatcher of Southeast Asian hill forest with a warm rufous breast and alert, upright posture. It perches conspicuously on exposed branches at the forest edge and sallies to catch flying insects. Found from the Malay Peninsula to the Philippines, it is a common component of hill forest bird communities.", photo: "https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/55230547/medium.jpg" },
  { name: "Verditer Flycatcher", fact: "A small flycatcher whose male is a striking all-over turquoise-blue — the vivid 'verdigris' copper colour inspiring its name. It perches on exposed wires and branches at forest edges and sings from the highest available perch. Found widely across South and Southeast Asia, it breeds in the Himalayas and winters across the subcontinent.", photo: "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/175806086/medium.jpg" },
];
